window.RELICS_BUNDLE = {"fortunes": {"benten": {"name": "Benten", "domain": "Fortune of romantic love", "kanji": "弁天"}, "bishamon": {"name": "Bishamon", "domain": "Fortune of strength", "kanji": "毘沙門"}, "daikoku": {"name": "Daikoku", "domain": "Fortune of wealth", "kanji": "大黒"}, "ebisu": {"name": "Ebisu", "domain": "Fortune of honest work", "kanji": "恵比寿"}, "fukurokujin": {"name": "Fukurokujin", "domain": "Fortune of wisdom and mercy", "kanji": "福禄寿"}, "hotei": {"name": "Hotei", "domain": "Fortune of contentment", "kanji": "布袋"}, "jurojin": {"name": "Jurojin", "domain": "Fortune of longevity", "kanji": "寿老人"}}, "relics": [{"slug": "basin-of-the-lapping-wave", "name": "The Basin of the Lapping Wave", "japanese_romaji": "Sazanami-no-Tarai", "japanese_kanji": "漣の盥", "fortune": "benten", "clan": "mantis", "temple": "a temple of Benten in Mantis lands", "named_entity": "Benten herself, whose emergence from the spring at Onogawa is locally attested; and the peasant pair Toshimi and Heigo, the salt-makers whose forty-year marriage outlasted shipwreck and exile", "relic_type": "water-feature (stone basin fed by a sacred spring)", "description": "A round basin of dark-grey stone, knee-high to a standing man and broad enough that a tall woman cannot reach her hands across its diameter without leaning. The stone is rough on its outer face and smooth-worn on its inner; the lip is grooved where the water trickles over a single low notch on the basin's eastern side and runs down a stone channel to the temple's lower garden. The basin sits at the center of an open court paved with grey beach-pebbles, beneath a wooden canopy on four cedar pillars; no walls enclose the court, and the wind from the harbor passes freely through it. The water in the basin is brackish — fed by a small spring beneath the temple foundations that mingles with the sea-water that seeps through the island's stone — and the surface is rarely still, even on windless days, for the spring beneath sends up a slow, irregular bubbling that disturbs the surface in patterns the eye cannot quite predict.\n\nThe spring beneath the basin is the spring of Onogawa, from which Benten is said to have emerged in the second age of the world, riding the back of a sea-dragon, and on the shore of which she first wept for the love of the mortal she could not keep. The spring was at the time on the mainland; the island of Kaimetsu Toshi rose around it in a great upheaval of the sea in the fourth century before the Empire, and the Mantis fishing-villages that became the city were settled around the spring as their first holy site. The basin was set above the spring by the first Yoritomo who took the city, perhaps eight hundred years past, and the temple was built around the basin a generation later. The basin has never been moved. The water has never run dry, not in the worst summers of the Mantis lands' memory, and has never overflowed its notch, not in the worst typhoon seasons either.\n\nThe basin is also a memorial to Toshimi and Heigo, salt-makers of a small fishing village on the eastern shore of the island, who lived three centuries past. Toshimi was the daughter of a salt-maker; Heigo was a fisherman who took up salt-making after marrying her. In the seventh year of their marriage Heigo was lost at sea in a sudden storm and presumed drowned; Toshimi raised their two children alone for eleven years, mourning him each spring at this basin. In the eighteenth year of the marriage Heigo returned — he had been carried by storm to the southern islands, taken as a slave by gaijin traders, and made his way home over the course of more than a decade through means he could never afterward fully recount. The temple records the day of his return as the day Benten's grace was made most visible to the village: Toshimi met him at the harbor and brought him to the basin and washed his hands and feet in its water before taking him home. They lived together another twenty-two years, and were buried in the temple's lower garden where the basin's water runs down into a small pool above their graves.\n\nA betrothed couple may petition the Custodian of Sacred Relics to be received at the basin. The Custodian leads them to the court at the hour of the rising tide — the time is determined by the temple's tide-tables, posted at the gate — and asks each of them to dip a single hand into the basin and bring up water to their lips. They drink. The Custodian does not speak during the dipping. The water tastes of salt and stone, and is not pleasant to the unprepared mouth.\n\nSome couples are graced, on tasting the water, with the surface of the basin briefly stilling beneath the spring's bubbling — a flat circle of calm appearing for the length of a breath, then breaking again into ripples. This is Benten's nod: the marriage is in her water and will keep. Some are graced with the water tasting sweet rather than salt — the spring's mineral signing to the couple that the bond is the bond of fresh water and not of salt, a long bond rather than a short bond, a bond for many seasons. Some couples find the water bitter or simply briny, and this is no failure — Benten is not in the habit of remaking what she has already blessed, and the bond will keep on its own merits. The Custodian does not interpret the taste at length; the couple is given a cloth to wipe their mouths, a small token of pebble from the court to carry away in their sleeve, and a brief blessing.\n\nThe basin is also the relic to which marriage and dowry disputes are brought in Kaimetsu Toshi. The temple is by long custom a referee for such disputes, called in by the city's magistrates when a marriage contract has gone wrong — the dowry partly delivered and partly withheld, the bride's family alleging mistreatment, the groom's family alleging deception, a betrothal broken and the question of which family must bear the loss. The Custodian of Sacred Relics receives the parties at the basin in the presence of the magistrate. Each party speaks their case across the basin, the water between them. They are then asked to each dip a hand and drink, as the betrothed do.\n\nThe dispute is not decided by the drinking. The decision is the magistrate's. But the temple watches closely how each party handles the water — whether they drink without grimace, whether their hand trembles at the lip of the basin, whether they look down into the water as they drink or away from it, whether the surface of the basin reacts to their dipping with calm or with sudden agitation. These signs are reported to the magistrate and weighed alongside the documents, witnesses, and reputations the magistrate has gathered. Benten, the Custodian will tell the magistrate, knows what each party has done; she will not always tell the temple what she knows, but she will tell it as she chooses, and the magistrate is welcome to listen. The Yoritomo and Yasuki merchant houses send their marriage-contract disputes to this court regularly. The judgments stick.\n\nSome parties — those whose case is clean — drink the water and find it sweet, and this is a sign read by the temple in their favor. Some parties find the water so bitter they cannot finish the dip without coughing, and this is a sign too. Some find the water unremarkable, and the temple takes from this only that Benten has chosen to be silent on the matter and that the magistrate must work the harder. The basin's signals are layered with the magistrate's own observation, the merchant ledgers, the testimony of go-betweens; the Custodian does not pretend the basin renders verdicts, and no verdict in living memory has rested on the basin alone.\n\nThe basin is also visited each spring on the seventh day after the equinox by the salt-makers of the island, who come in procession with small wooden boxes of new-season salt and pour a measure of salt into the basin in Toshimi's name. The water of the basin is then dipped out by the salt-makers in turn and used to wet the first rakings of the new salt-pans for the year. The temple does not record the yield each year, but the salt-makers do, and the yield in years when the basin's salt-blessing has been given on a day of unusual stillness is said by them to exceed the yield of years when the spring was restless.\n\nThe water cannot be removed from the basin in bulk; the spring will not give what is not asked of it properly. The temple workshop produces small clay bottles into which a single dipping of the water is poured, sealed with wax, and blessed; these bottles are carried by sailors of the Mantis fleet, by traders sailing from Kaimetsu Toshi to the mainland, and by couples about to be parted by long sea voyage. The wax is not to be broken until the voyager returns home and presents the bottle to their spouse at their own threshold. The bottles that have been broken before such a return are kept by the Custodian in a small chest beneath the basin's canopy; there are perhaps thirty of them, and the temple does not say what became of those who broke them.\n\nThe basin cannot be moved. The Yoritomo daimyo of three generations past, in a season of pride, proposed that the basin be relocated to a more impressive court on higher ground in the new wing of the temple. The temple replied, formally and politely, that the spring beneath the basin had been in its place since the second age of the world and that the temple had been built where it was for the spring's sake, not the spring placed where it was for the temple's sake. The proposal was withdrawn. The basin sits where it has always sat."}, {"slug": "half-mirror-of-soshi-otomi", "name": "The Half-Mirror of Soshi Otomi", "japanese_romaji": "Wakare-Kagami", "japanese_kanji": "別れ鏡", "fortune": "benten", "clan": "scorpion", "temple": "a temple of Benten in Scorpion lands", "named_entity": "Soshi Otomi (Scorpion shugenja-widow of the early seventh century, who carried her husband's name forty years and was reunited with his half of their wedding mirror only at her death)", "relic_type": "token (half of a broken bronze hand-mirror, paired with its mate)", "description": "A bronze hand-mirror, broken cleanly down its middle along an old fault in the casting, the two halves now joined again and held together by a fine collar of silver wirework that runs around the rim and across the break. The mirrored face is dim with age and shows a clouded image rather than a clear one; the back is incised with a pattern of two cranes flying in opposite directions around a sprig of plum-blossom. The handle is wrapped in dark silk. The mirror rests on a black silk cushion in a shallow tray of polished river-pebbles, in a small chamber at the back of the temple beside the wall that faces the city's eastern river. A single candle burns in a brass holder above the tray. The candle is not relit when it goes out — a new candle is set each evening at the seventh bell, and the chamber takes its light from whichever candle is presently burning.\n\nSoshi Otomi was the wife of Bayushi Tadatsugu, a Scorpion magistrate of the early seventh century, and was widowed in her twenty-ninth year when Tadatsugu was killed on circuit in the western provinces. Before he left on what would be his last journey, the two of them broke their wedding mirror in the manner of the old Scorpion custom — each took one half, the husband to carry on his travels and the wife to keep at her writing-desk, and the halves were to be rejoined at every reunion. Tadatsugu's half was returned to her with his other effects after his death. She did not rejoin the halves. She kept them apart on her desk, one before her and one behind her, for forty years; she did not remarry; she kept Tadatsugu's name and his household as she had received it; she took the tonsure of the Soshi shugenja and entered the temple of Benten at Ryoko Owari in her sixty-eighth year. On the night of her death in her seventy-first year she asked her attending novice to bring her both halves of the mirror. The novice fetched them. Otomi joined them, edge to edge, on the cushion beneath her hand, and died with the mirror whole.\n\nThe silver collar was added by the temple workshop the year after her death, to hold the join Otomi had made. The temple has never separated the halves again.\n\nA pilgrim recently widowed, or long-separated from a spouse by exile, or estranged by a quarrel they wish to repair, or a couple who must be parted for years by Imperial posting, may petition the Custodian of Sacred Relics to be received at the chamber. The Custodian leads the pilgrim into the chamber, asks them to kneel beside the tray, and recites a short prayer to Benten. The Custodian then touches the silver collar at the seam of the mirror with one finger and asks the pilgrim to look into the mirror's face. The image is clouded; what the pilgrim sees there is what Benten wishes them to see.\n\nThe recently widowed are graced, in some cases, with a glimpse of the absent spouse looking back at them — not the spouse as they were at the moment of death, but the spouse as they were in some private moment of the marriage, a turning of the head or a half-smile across the breakfast table. The image is gone in an instant. The pilgrim is not asked to describe what they saw, and the Custodian does not record what they say if they choose to speak. Some pilgrims see no image at all in the mirror, and the Custodian counsels them that Benten is not done with the marriage, that the absent spouse is still close, and that the pilgrim is not yet a widow in the sense the temple uses the word.\n\nThe long-separated are graced with a different gift. A samurai whose spouse is posted to the far provinces, who has not seen them in years, may be granted in the clouded face a momentary clearing — the mirror going briefly bright, the brass shining as if newly polished. This is Benten signaling that the spouse, in that moment, has thought of the pilgrim; the pilgrim is to write to their spouse that night, knowing the letter will be welcome. Records of these signs are kept in the temple ledger, and on more than one occasion the husband and the wife have written to one another on the same night across a thousand *ri*, the letters crossing in the post.\n\nThe estranged are graced, sometimes, with finding their own face in the mirror split along the silver collar — half on one side of the seam, half on the other, the join of the silver running through their reflected forehead. This is a hard grace. It tells the pilgrim that the quarrel is not in the spouse but in themselves, that they have been carrying the broken mirror as Otomi did, and that the repair is theirs to make. The Custodian sits with such pilgrims at length afterward.\n\nSome pilgrims see only their own face in the clouded mirror, no clearing, no doubling, no glimpse — and this is no failure. Benten has been content to look. The marriage is in her hand whether or not she shows it.\n\nThe mirror cannot be separated. The temple workshop has, on rare occasions, commissioned bronze hand-mirrors broken at the time of casting for couples about to be parted by long Imperial duty; these are sold to families who wish to keep the old Scorpion custom Otomi kept, and a senior monk blesses each pair at the chamber before they are taken away. The replicas are common enough in the Shosuro and Bayushi households of Ryoko Owari. The original is not one of them. It has been whole now for over a century, and will remain whole.\n\nWhen the city of Ryoko Owari is troubled — when a great fire passes through the eastern wards, when the river floods the temple's lower steps, when the Shosuro daimyo or the Bayushi households suffer some severe and unexpected sorrow — the candle above the tray is said to gutter without draft, and the silver collar around the mirror's seam to dim. The Custodian inspects the chamber at the seventh bell every evening for this reason. In the four decades since the silver was set, the candle has guttered six times. Each time, within a season, the city has been visited by a sorrow of marriages — a great household broken, a notable widowing, a chain of failed betrothals among the ruling lineages. Otomi watches over Ryoko Owari's marriages from her side of the silver, and the temple takes her watch as a kindness, even when what she shows them is a sorrow on the way."}, {"slug": "marriage-stones-of-hokke-tomotsugu-and-sayuri", "name": "The Marriage Stones of Hokke Tomotsugu and Sayuri", "japanese_romaji": "Chigiri-no-Ishi", "japanese_kanji": "契りの石", "fortune": "benten", "clan": "fox", "temple": "a temple of Benten in Fox lands", "named_entity": "Hokke Tomotsugu (Fox samurai of the ruling lineage) and Sayuri (peasant woman), seven generations past", "relic_type": "pair (river stones in lacquered case)", "description": "Two smooth river stones, each the size of a small peach, one slightly darker than the other. They rest in a small lacquered case lined with pale silk. The case is open by day and closed by night, displayed on a low table beside a stone water-basin in a small garden alcove off the temple's main hall — water is Benten's element, and the alcove is built around a slow trickle of stream-water that runs through a copper trough into the basin.\n\nThe stones were taken from a stream in the upper reaches of Kitsune Mori, where Hokke Tomotsugu and Sayuri first spoke to one another some seven generations past. Tomotsugu was a son of the Hokke lineage's ruling house, sent into the forest in his eighteenth year for meditation. Sayuri was a peasant woman of a hamlet near the stream, who came each morning to do her village's laundry on a flat stone there. They met by accident, spoke awkwardly, and then arranged to keep meeting — for three years, with the patience of those who know their love is not going to be permitted.\n\nWhen they wished to marry, the Hokke daimyo refused the match, as both knew he would; Sayuri's village would not have honored an unblessed union, and the Hokke would not have honored a peasant daughter-in-law. The couple eloped to a Temple of Benten in the Fox lands, which had even then a reputation as a sanctuary for marriages the families would not bless. They each took a stone from their stream, walked the three-day pilgrimage in silence, exchanged the stones at the temple as wedding gifts, and were married privately by a Benten priest. They lived as outcasts for two years before Sayuri bore Tomotsugu a son. The Hokke daimyo, by then older and quieter, accepted the boy, and through him the marriage. The couple lived to old age together. After both had died — Tomotsugu first, in his eighty-fourth year, and Sayuri eleven years later — the stones were brought to the temple by their grandchildren and donated.\n\nA betrothed couple, or a long-married couple in difficulty, or two people who acknowledge an affection that cannot become a marriage, may petition the Custodian of Sacred Relics to hold the stones. The Custodian opens the lacquered case in their presence and asks each to take a stone in their cupped hand — the darker stone is given to the elder of the two by tradition, but no one minds if the giving is reversed. The pilgrims speak the words of their bond aloud, or, if they cannot, speak silently with only Benten as their witness. They then exchange the stones, each placing their stone into the cupped hand of the other. The Custodian returns the stones to the case after a moment of stillness. The whole ceremony takes less than the time of a long breath, and the pilgrims leave by the garden gate rather than the way they entered.\n\nSome pairs of pilgrims are graced with the stone they receive being warm to the touch — Benten's blessing on the bond they have spoken. Some are graced with the stone bearing a faint impression of the other's grip when it is returned to them, a singular omen of two becoming one. Some find the stones merely smooth and cool, no different from any other river stone, and this is no failure — Benten is content to witness without ornament, and a quiet ceremony is still a ceremony. Some are graced with an unease while holding their stone, a chill or a heaviness — the Custodian receives the stones back gently in this case, and afterward asks the pilgrims whether they have spoken their bond fully and truly. The conversation is not a judgment; it is a kindness.\n\nThe stones cannot be replicated. The temple workshop does not produce replicas, for Benten's blessing in this relic is the singular pair and not the class of paired stones. Couples who marry at the temple may, however, carry away a small carved wooden token from the workshop, into which a senior monk has written the date of the marriage and a benediction; these tokens are common in the wardrobe-chests and small altars of married couples throughout the Fox lands.\n\nThe stones are very rarely allowed to travel. When two parties of unusual circumstance are to be joined — a marriage between two former enemies whose families have agreed to peace, a reunion of two estranged Fox lineages through a child, the reconciliation of a couple long separated by a shameful event — the Custodian of Sacred Relics may accompany the stones to the wedding under formal escort and bring them home the same evening. This is rare. In the past century the stones have left the temple in this way only nine times. They have not failed to return."}, {"slug": "sealed-letters-of-bayushi-renjiro-and-shosuro-aiko", "name": "The Sealed Letters of Bayushi Renjiro and Shosuro Aiko", "japanese_romaji": "Fuuin-no-Koibumi", "japanese_kanji": "封印の恋文", "fortune": "benten", "clan": "scorpion", "temple": "a temple of Benten in Scorpion lands", "named_entity": "Bayushi Renjiro and Shosuro Aiko, an estranged samurai pair of the late sixth century whose reconciliation was discovered only in their letters after both had died", "relic_type": "written material (bundled love letters, partly sealed)", "description": "A bundle of forty-one letters on undyed *washi* paper, tied with a single faded red cord, kept in a black lacquered box on a low table in a small reading-room off the temple's eastern courtyard. The box has no lock. Twenty-three of the letters in the bundle are unsealed, their folds opened and refolded so many times the paper has gone soft at the creases; eighteen remain sealed, the wax red and unbroken, the recipient's name written across each seal in a careful hand. The reading-room is small enough for six listeners and one reader, no more, and the paper screens of its windows are kept closed by day so that the only light is the lamp at the reader's elbow. A second lamp is kept burning in a niche beside the box; this lamp is never allowed to go out.\n\nBayushi Renjiro and Shosuro Aiko were married in the late sixth century by arrangement of their families — Renjiro a third son of a Bayushi vassal lineage, Aiko a magistrate's daughter of the Shosuro. The marriage went badly in its first year. Aiko was posted to a magistrate's office in the western provinces; Renjiro remained in the Scorpion capital in the household of his father-in-law. They quarreled before her departure and did not speak again face-to-face for the remaining nineteen years of their lives. They wrote — first formally, in the matter of household affairs, and then, slowly, as the years went by, in matters that were no longer formal. The forty-one letters in this bundle are the love letters that grew from that correspondence: not the household letters, not the duty letters, but the letters between two people who had married in anger and then, across a great distance, found that they had been writing themselves into love with one another.\n\nThey never met again. Aiko died of a fever in her fourteenth year of separation; Renjiro learned of her death by Imperial post and survived her by five years, during which he wrote the last eighteen letters in the bundle — letters addressed to her, sealed, never sent, kept in the lacquered box she had given him at their wedding. After Renjiro's death the box was opened by his nephew, who read enough to understand what he held, then closed the box and brought it to the temple. The temple took the box and the letters, refused the nephew's offer of payment, and made a place for them in the reading-room where they now rest. The eighteen sealed letters have never been opened. They will not be.\n\nThree times each year — at the opening of spring, at the Festival of the Long Cord in autumn, and on the seventh day of the second winter month, which is the day Aiko's last letter was written — the Custodian of Sacred Relics convenes a small reading. A pilgrim, or a married couple, or a group of betrothed cousins together, or a courtier sent at the request of a daimyo whose marriage is in difficulty, may petition to attend. The Custodian draws a single unsealed letter from the bundle by touch, without looking, and reads it aloud. The reading is slow. The Custodian does not gloss the difficult passages, and does not explain who is writing or in what year. The listener is left to receive the letter as if it had been addressed to them.\n\nSome who hear a letter find that it speaks to their own marriage with such precision that they cannot afterward remember whether they were the listener or the addressee. Some hear a letter about a quarrel they themselves have not had, and the Custodian asks them to consider whether the quarrel is one they have been preparing without knowing. Some are graced with a faint warmth in the red cord that ties the bundle when the letter is returned, the cord briefly the color of fresh blood rather than faded; this is Aiko's grace upon a marriage that may still be rescued. Some are graced with the second lamp in the niche flaring without draft as the letter is finished, the small fire reaching upward as if to take a breath, and this is Renjiro acknowledging that the lesson has been received. Some hear a letter that does not speak to them at all, and this is no failure — Benten has spoken in other languages on other days, and the pilgrim may return when the season is more apt.\n\nThe eighteen sealed letters are read only by Benten. The temple does not open them. The wax is unbroken on all of them, the seals dark with age, the names of the addressee written across the wax in Renjiro's hand. The Custodian holds the sealed letters during the reading-out of the unsealed ones, and may, if the listener's burden is great, place a sealed letter against the listener's forehead for the length of one breath. The listener does not learn what is written. The letter speaks past the wax in whatever language Benten chooses, and the listener carries away what was given without knowing what it was. Pilgrims who have received this gift describe a curious lightness afterward — they speak of a thing they had been carrying that they no longer carry, but cannot name what it was.\n\nThe letters are also brought out, twice in a generation perhaps, in cases of estrangement among the Scorpion lineages where a marriage has broken and a daimyo wishes to know whether reconciliation is possible. The Custodian of Sacred Relics travels with the bundle to the household in question under formal escort. A single letter is read aloud to the estranged pair in the presence of their families. The Custodian does not advise, and does not offer interpretation. The Scorpion are a clan that hears well; they are trusted to hear what they are given.\n\nThe letters cannot leave the box, and the box cannot leave the reading-room except for the household readings described above. The temple workshop produces *replica letters* on request — short copied passages from the unsealed correspondence, transcribed by senior monks and blessed at the table, taken home by Scorpion couples to be read aloud on the seventh day of each month at their family altars. The replicas are common in Scorpion households throughout the southern provinces. The originals are read only here, only by Benten's appointed voice, only when the season is right.\n\nWhen the bundle is returned to the box, the red cord is retied by the Custodian's own hand. The cord has not been replaced in the four generations the temple has held the letters. Some have asked whether the cord will outlast the paper, and the temple's answer is that the cord will outlast whatever it must."}, {"slug": "three-cups-of-kakita-hokuto", "name": "The Three Cups of Kakita Hokuto", "japanese_romaji": "San-San-no-Sakazuki", "japanese_kanji": "三々の盃", "fortune": "benten", "clan": "crane", "temple": "a temple of Benten in Crane lands", "named_entity": "Kakita Hokuto (Kakita ceremonialist of the fourth century, who codified the san-san-kudo cup-ritual still used at Crane weddings)", "relic_type": "implement (set of three lacquered wedding cups, nested)", "description": "Three lacquered cups of *urushi* over thin cedar, nested one inside the other, smallest at the top and largest at the base. Each cup is finished in deep red lacquer on the outside and pale gold on the inside; each is rimmed in fine silver. The smallest cup is the diameter of a child's palm, the middle cup the diameter of a woman's palm, the largest the diameter of a tall man's palm. On the gold interior of each cup, painted in the finest brushwork, is a single flying crane — the smallest cup's crane in flight rising, the middle cup's crane in flight level, the largest cup's crane in flight descending. The set rests on a low table of cherrywood in a side chamber off the main hall. A small ewer of unglazed pottery sits beside the cups; it holds the rice-wine used in the ritual when the cups are taken into service.\n\nKakita Hokuto was a ceremonialist of the Kakita family in the fourth century, the year-records do not name his parents but record him as the third of three brothers, all of whom served the family in court ritual. Hokuto codified the *san-san-kudo* — the three-times-three exchange of cups that is at the heart of every Crane wedding to this day. He did not invent the rite; the threefold exchange existed before him in older and looser forms. Hokuto's gift was to fix it: three cups, three sips from each cup, three exchanges between bride and groom, the order of sips and exchanges precisely arranged so that the rite would carry the bond from heaven to earth to heaven again in a single closed circuit. He served four Crane daimyo as their wedding-master across forty-six years, performed the cup-ritual at more than a thousand weddings, and presented these cups — the cups he had carried in his sleeve to every wedding of his career — to this Temple of Benten in his sixty-third year, three years before his death.\n\nThe cups have been used in Crane weddings since. They are not the only cups used; most weddings use cups commissioned for the occasion from the lacquer workshops of the lower city. The Three Cups of Kakita Hokuto are reserved for weddings of unusual significance — the wedding of the Doji daimyo's child, the wedding of a Kakita daimyo, the wedding of an Imperial cousin to a Crane, the wedding that closes a great peace between Crane and another clan. The Custodian of Sacred Relics carries the cups in a black-lacquered carrying case under formal escort to the wedding, performs the *san-san-kudo* with the bride and groom himself or hands the cups to the officiating priest of the family with appropriate ceremony, and returns the cups to the temple the same evening. They have been carried out one hundred and twelve times since Hokuto's gift; the temple has the record of each occasion in its ceremonial ledgers, with the names of the couples and the date of every wedding.\n\nIn the season between the first warm rain of spring and the equinox — which is the start of the Crane wedding season — the cups are also brought out for the **Blessing of the Engaged**. On the first dragon-day of that season the Custodian opens the case in the temple's main hall, sets the cups on a low table beneath the hall's central beam, and pours wine into the largest cup. Betrothed couples come to the hall in turn through the day, kneel before the table, and each sips three times from the largest cup — bride first, then groom, then bride again — before bowing and giving way to the next couple. The wine is not refilled between couples; the same wine is sipped through the day by every betrothed pair in attendance, perhaps two hundred couples in a busy spring. The cup is wiped between sippers with a square of white silk. The other two cups are not used in this rite; they sit beside the largest, lids off, witnesses to the day.\n\nSome couples find, after their three sips from Hokuto's largest cup, that small habits of speech between them ease. They begin to anticipate one another's silences more skillfully than they had before; they find themselves laughing more often at the same small things; they find, when the marriage is concluded later that season, that the first months of it are gentler than they had been warned to expect. Benten settles into the household with the wine she has tasted, and there is much that is easier in such houses for some years afterward. Some are graced with feeling the lacquer of the cup warm against their lip as they sip — Hokuto's hand, the temple says, warming the cup that he carried so long. Some are graced with seeing the painted crane on the cup's interior seem briefly to turn its head toward them as the wine recedes. Many feel nothing in particular and only sip a fine wine from a fine cup, and this too is a blessing — Benten is content to be quiet, and Hokuto's rite carries her blessing as fully whether or not the cup performs theatrically.\n\nWhen the cups are used at a wedding, the threefold exchange is performed exactly as Hokuto recorded it in his ceremonial papers, which are kept in the temple library and consulted before each carrying-out. The order of sips, the angle at which the cup is presented, the silk that lines the carrying case, the pattern of the ribbon that ties the case: all of these are reproduced as Hokuto left them. The temple does not deviate. Couples who request alterations to the rite for their own reasons — and such requests are made, especially among the modern Doji — receive replicas commissioned from the workshop. The replicas are good, and the wedding is honored, but the Three Cups are not bent to the convenience of any wedding.\n\nThe cups have been damaged once. In the fourth generation after Hokuto's death, the largest cup was dropped by a junior Custodian during a wedding at a great Doji house and chipped at its rim. The Custodian was reassigned to the temple library; the cup was repaired by the lacquer workshop with red urushi and fine gold dust along the line of the chip, and the repair is now a faint gold streak along the cup's rim, visible in lamplight if one looks for it. The temple has come to consider the gold streak a part of the cup, and a quiet teaching: that a marriage is not destroyed by a chip, and that a careful repair becomes part of the beauty of the long bond.\n\nThe cups cannot leave the temple except for the formal weddings described above. Replica sets are commissioned from the workshop in some numbers each year, and Crane lineages of any standing keep a set of *san-san-kudo* cups in their household altar; the family wedding-master uses these cups at the wedding of each child, and the cups pass down in the lineage. The originals are not the model for these replicas in any meaningful sense — they are the original from which every Crane wedding for nine centuries has descended in unbroken succession, and they sit in the side chamber as the still center of that descent."}, {"slug": "wedding-biwa-of-doji-fumika", "name": "The Wedding Biwa of Doji Fumika", "japanese_romaji": "Konrei-no-Biwa", "japanese_kanji": "婚礼の琵琶", "fortune": "benten", "clan": "crane", "temple": "a temple of Benten in Crane lands", "named_entity": "Doji Fumika (Crane court composer of the early seventh century, who set the marriage songs still sung at Crane weddings)", "relic_type": "instrument (biwa lute)", "description": "A four-stringed *biwa* of paulownia wood, its body the shape of a teardrop and the color of pale honey, with a narrow neck of darker rosewood and a tortoiseshell plectrum-rest worn smooth by use. The five frets are tied in silk cord that has been replaced perhaps twenty times across the centuries, always by the same workshop in the lower city. The strings are silk, and are restrung at the beginning of each spring at the Mending Ceremony — the old strings are not discarded but kept in a small lacquered box beneath the display, for any one of them may have been the string that sounded a particular blessing in a particular wedding. The biwa rests upright on a low stand of cherry wood, behind a sheer silk curtain, in an alcove off the main hall of the temple. A shallow basin of water set into the stone floor before the alcove catches the candle-light and throws it gently up against the curtain.\n\nDoji Fumika was a court composer in the early seventh century, the third daughter of a minor Doji lineage and a student of the Kakita musical academy. She composed for the wedding of the Doji daimyo's eldest daughter when she was twenty-three, and the songs she wrote for that wedding so pleased the assembled courts of both families that they were performed at the next great Crane wedding, and the next, until they became the marriage-songs which are still sung at Crane weddings throughout the Empire. Fumika herself never married. She lived sixty-one years, composed perhaps ninety songs of which thirty survive, and on the day of her death asked that her biwa be given to the temple of Benten — for Benten, she said, had given her every song, and the biwa belonged in Benten's house.\n\nThe biwa is played twice a year — at the Festival of First Promise in early spring, when betrothals are formally announced in the Crane courts, and at the Festival of the Long Cord in autumn, when long-married couples renew their bonds before Benten. A senior monk of the temple, chosen for her skill on the instrument as much as for her standing in the order, draws the biwa from behind the silk curtain and plays one of Fumika's wedding-songs through from beginning to end. The Custodian of Sacred Relics waits beside her, takes the biwa from her at the song's end, and returns it to its stand. The played string is then replaced before the next festival; the song is not played twice from the same string.\n\nThe biwa is also carried in procession at the weddings of the ruling Doji house, and at certain other Crane weddings of unusual import — the marriage of a Doji to a Kakita that joins two lineages, the marriage of a Crane daimyo's child to a Scorpion peace-bride, the marriage of a widowed Crane lord to a second wife who brings reconciliation between estranged branches. The Custodian of Sacred Relics travels with the biwa under formal escort, plays the chosen song at the wedding feast, and returns the biwa to the temple the same night. The biwa has been carried out of the temple in this way forty-seven times since Fumika's death.\n\nSome couples are graced, at their wedding or at the festivals, with a particular sweetness in the played note — a clarity that catches in the breath of those listening, that sets the older guests weeping for the weddings of their own youth. This is Benten's voice running beneath Fumika's, and it falls on the couple as a blessing on the long years they will share. Some are graced with finding, in the days after the song, that small disagreements between them resolve more easily than they expected, that they speak more freely to one another, that they remember more often why they first agreed to marry. Some hear only a fine biwa well-played, and this is no failure — Benten is content to bless quietly, and many of the longest marriages in the Crane lands began in quiet.\n\nWhen the biwa is to be played, the senior monk fasts for the preceding day and bathes in the temple's south spring at dawn. She does not speak from the time she rises until the first note of the song. She does not play the biwa at any other time, and she does not teach others to play it — when she grows old, the temple selects a successor from among the senior monks and the Kakita academy is consulted on her musical training, but the successor does not touch this biwa until the previous player has died or formally laid the office down. The biwa cannot be played by an unwed monk who has known no love; this is not a rule but a practical matter, for Fumika's songs were written from the heart of one who had loved without marrying, and they ask of their player the same depth. The temple has on three occasions left the biwa unplayed for a festival because no monk in the order was prepared to play it — a quiet sorrow each time, but a more reverent one than playing it ill.\n\nThe biwa cannot leave the temple except for the processional weddings described above. The replicas commissioned from the workshop — biwas of paulownia and rosewood, made to Fumika's pattern, blessed at the alcove before being sent out — are taken by Crane lineages and by Kakita musical houses, and Fumika's songs are taught from these replicas. The original is a witness to those songs, not their source."}, {"slug": "broken-yari-of-the-oni-no-yasuhiro", "name": "The Broken Yari of the Oni no Yasuhiro", "japanese_romaji": "Ware-Yari", "japanese_kanji": "割れ槍", "fortune": "bishamon", "clan": "crab", "temple": "a temple of Bishamon in Crab lands", "named_entity": "the oni once known as Yasuhiro, defeated at the southern marches by Hiruma Tatsumune in the late second century", "relic_type": "weapon (broken spear-haft and head, taken from a defeated enemy)", "description": "A broken yari of unusual make. The haft is a man's height in length, of a dense black wood that has not been identified by the temple's carvers, snapped clean across two-thirds of the way to the head. The break is recent in appearance though it is over four hundred years old — the splintered fibers within the haft are still pale, as if the break had been made yesterday. The spear-head is of an iron darker than ordinary forge-iron, the edges nicked in three places, the tang bound to the broken haft by iron wire taken from the original binding. The weapon rests on a stone slab within a barred iron cage in the lower chamber of the temple, where the floor is cut from the bedrock and a single lamp of fish-oil burns at all hours.\n\nThe yari was taken in the late second century by Hiruma Tatsumune from a creature that had once been a samurai named Yasuhiro. The history is set down in the temple's records as Tatsumune reported it: a Hida vassal of the lower marches named Yasuhiro was lost on a patrol south of the line in his twenty-eighth year, returned in his thirty-first as something that wore his face and carried his name, and was killed by his cousin Tatsumune at the cost of three of Tatsumune's men. The thing that had been Yasuhiro fought with this yari, which Tatsumune broke across his cousin's shield in the final exchange before the killing stroke. Tatsumune carried the broken yari to this Temple of Bishamon rather than burn it with the body, on the counsel of a Kuni shugenja who held that the weapon's strength was Bishamon's by right and ought not to be lost to the southern fires. The Order has kept it under bar and lamp since.\n\nThe yari is brought out once each year, on the third day of the Festival of the Wall — the festival the Hiruma keep in honor of the line that holds the southern marches — for the **Blessing of the Arms**. The Custodian of Sacred Relics carries the broken yari from its cage to the temple's outer training yard, where the captains of the Hiruma patrols and the senior bushi of the Wall have assembled with their own weapons laid before them. The Custodian sets the yari on its slab at the head of the line, and the captains pass before it one by one, each laying his weapon for a moment against the broken haft before reclaiming it. Bishamon's strength is in the weapon that was wrested from the enemy and turned against him; the strength is shared with the weapons that touch it, and the captains who pass before the yari carry that strength back into the field.\n\nThe yari does not give its blessing to every weapon. Some captains find their own blades warmer in their hand when they reclaim them — an auspicious omen that Yasuhiro's strength has been turned against the southern fires in their hand for the coming year. Some find nothing remarkable, and this is not held against them; the yari gives its blessing as Bishamon wills, and a captain who is not graced this year may be graced the next. Some weapons placed against the haft are found to slip from their owner's grip when reclaimed, and the temple holds this as a quiet sign that the captain has been carrying his weapon poorly and ought to consult the smith before the campaign season. The captains who have heeded this sign have not regretted it.\n\nThe yari cannot be destroyed. The Kuni shugenja who counseled Tatsumune left a writing on this matter, kept in the temple's archive: the thing that had been Yasuhiro left some residue in the weapon, and to burn or break the weapon further would be to free that residue into the world rather than keep it bound. The temple does not invite Kuni inspection more often than once a generation, and on those occasions the inspecting shugenja has reported that the binding holds and the residue is quiet. The lamp of fish-oil is kept burning because the fish-oil is the lamp the second-century shugenja specified, and the temple has not seen reason to substitute.\n\nThe yari cannot leave the temple. The Hiruma have asked at moments of grave threat — most recently during the long winter of the present century, when the southern marches were pressed harder than at any time in living memory — and the abbots have refused. The yari does its work where it is. The Blessing of the Arms is its outward gift; the cage and the lamp are its inward labor. To carry the weapon out would be to risk breaking the binding the Kuni set, and no captain's strength is worth that cost."}, {"slug": "kabuto-of-hida-morinosuke", "name": "The Kabuto of Hida Morinosuke", "japanese_romaji": "Iwakabe-no-Kabuto", "japanese_kanji": "岩壁の兜", "fortune": "bishamon", "clan": "crab", "temple": "a temple of Bishamon in Crab lands", "named_entity": "Hida Morinosuke (Hida wall-captain of the late third century, defender of the Stone Gate)", "relic_type": "armor piece (kabuto, war-helm)", "description": "A heavy iron *kabuto* of the old Hida pattern — five overlapping plates riveted to the bowl, a deep neck-guard of laced iron scales, a half-mask of beaten iron with the lower jaw left bare. The crest is a single rough boar's-tusk of cracked ivory, set into a bronze socket at the brow. The bowl is dented inward over the left ear in a fist-sized hollow that has not been hammered out — the blow that made it killed the oni that struck it, and the Hida who recovered the helm afterward chose to leave the dent. The kabuto sits on a heavy oaken stand within a stone alcove off the temple's commanders' hall, where a single iron lamp burns above it day and night.\n\nHida Morinosuke was a wall-captain at the Stone Gate in the late third century, in a generation when the gate was still raw stone and the inner courses had not yet been finished by Kaiu engineers. During the assault that the Hida call the Year of the Three Onis, Morinosuke held the gate's inner court for four days against a host that had broken the outer wall, refusing to fall back to the keep though his daimyo had given him leave to do so. On the fourth day he met the largest of the three onis at the inner gate itself, and the helm took the stroke that the oni had meant for his skull. He killed the oni with the broken end of his yari and lived long enough to see the relief column climb the steps. He died of his wounds before the gate was secured, the helm still on his head; the Kaiu who unbuckled it afterward could not pry the dent back into shape, and ordered the helm sent to the Order of Bishamon rather than reforged.\n\nA Hida wall-captain who is to take command of a contested gate, a section of the Wall under assault, or a fortified pass in the southern marches may petition the Custodian of Sacred Relics for the **Wearing of the Helm**. The Custodian leads the captain into the alcove, lifts the helm from its stand, and places it on the captain's head with the cords loose. The captain kneels with the helm and meditates for the duration of a stick of incense. Morinosuke's resolve attends the meditation, and the captain who is to hold a gate may take into himself some measure of the resolve by which Morinosuke held his.\n\nThe Custodian does not bind the cords. The captain wears the helm only loosely, only for the meditation, and removes it himself when the incense has burned out. To bind the cords would be to take Morinosuke's role rather than his counsel, and Morinosuke's role was given in his time and is not given again. The helm is then returned to its stand. Some captains rise from the meditation with the clear understanding of where their line must stand and where it may give; some rise with the certainty that they will not retreat from the position they are assigned, and have not retreated; some rise with the knowledge that they must request more men, and have learned from Morinosuke the courage to make the request without shame. Some are graced with the smell of cold stone in the alcove, though the alcove is dry — an auspicious omen that Morinosuke is present and approves.\n\nThe temple keeps a record of every captain who has worn the helm. The records go back to the third century and contain the captain's name, the gate or position he was to hold, and the outcome of the holding, as later reported. The records are not displayed; they are kept in the temple's archive for the use of the Stewards. The Custodian sometimes consults them when a captain petitions, to see what Morinosuke has answered to similar petitions in the past, but the consultation is the Custodian's discernment and not a binding precedent. Morinosuke's strength is given as he wills it given, and the records are an aid to understanding, not a tally.\n\nThe kabuto cannot leave the temple. The Hida house has asked twice in the past four centuries — once during the Tsume assault on the southern provinces, once during a feud among the vassal houses — and the abbots of those generations refused. The helm holds gates; it does not march. A captain who has worn it carries Morinosuke's resolve outward into the field; the helm itself remains on its stand so that the next captain may also kneel. To carry the helm to a battle would be to risk losing the dent, and the dent is the relic — the empty space where Morinosuke took the stroke and lived long enough to win."}, {"slug": "makiwara-post-of-ikoma-tadanari", "name": "The Makiwara Post of Ikoma Tadanari", "japanese_romaji": "Sennichi-no-Hashira", "japanese_kanji": "千日の柱", "fortune": "bishamon", "clan": "lion", "temple": "a temple of Bishamon in Lion lands", "named_entity": "Ikoma Tadanari (Ikoma bushi and lay-monk, late second century, founder of the Ikoma striking-form)", "relic_type": "training implement (makiwara striking-post)", "description": "A weathered post of dense red oak, the thickness of a man's thigh, planted upright in a square of packed earth within an open-air alcove off the temple's training yard. The post stands to chest height; its striking face is wrapped in many layers of rice-straw rope, the outermost layer fresh and the inner layers brown and brittle, the whole bound by a single hemp cord knotted at the back. The earth around the post is bare and hard from generations of bare feet. A simple cedar roof on four pillars shelters the post from rain, but the alcove is otherwise open to the air.\n\nIkoma Tadanari was an Ikoma bushi of the late second century who, after a campaign in his thirty-eighth year that cost him the use of his sword-arm, took lay-vows at this Temple of Bishamon and devoted the remainder of his life to the study of the striking-arts. He could no longer hold a katana, but he could still strike with the heel of his hand and with the open palm, and he developed in the last thirty years of his life a form of unarmed striking that the Ikoma school still teaches under the name *Tadanari-no-Te*. He struck this post — then a young post he had planted himself in the temple's yard — every morning for the last twenty-seven years of his life, a thousand strikes a day, the count tallied by an acolyte assigned to him by the temple. The post is the same post; the straw has been replaced by every Custodian since, the cord renewed each spring, but the oak heartwood is Tadanari's.\n\nA samurai of any clan who is to fight a duel, contest a tournament, or take part in a *taryū-jiai* between schools may, by tradition that predates the temple's records, come to the alcove and strike the post one hundred times in the hour before the contest. The temple makes no formal grant of permission for this — the alcove is open during daylight, and the post is for those who come. The Custodian of Sacred Relics observes the visitors from the inner gallery but does not interfere. Bishamon's strength is in the hand that has struck the post; the strength that the post has gathered from Tadanari and from the thousands of hands that have followed his may pass into the striker for the work that follows.\n\nSome samurai are graced with finding the post warmer to the touch than the morning air would suggest — an auspicious omen, signifying that Tadanari is present and lends his attention to the coming contest. Some find the straw wrapping unusually firm beneath their palms, as if the post answered back; this is read as Tadanari approving the form of the striking. Some find their hand reddening more quickly than they had expected, and the Custodian, if asked, will say that Tadanari has noted a weakness in the striker's stance and that the hand has paid for what the stance has not yet learned to carry. Most strikers feel only the post and the count and their own breath, and this is no failure; Tadanari taught a thousand strikes a day for twenty-seven years before he claimed to have learned anything, and the temple does not ask its visitors to do better than its founder.\n\nThe hundred-strike practice is the common rite, but the post serves longer purposes also. A novice of the Ikoma striking-school, at the time he is to be confirmed as a journeyman of the form, performs the **Thousand-Strike Vigil** at the post — a single day's work from before dawn to after dusk, the count kept by his sensei. The vigil is recorded in the school's roll. The roll has been kept for four centuries and contains every journeyman the Ikoma have produced; the temple's Steward of Records keeps the count and a copy of the roll is in the temple archive. The vigil is not given to every novice — some are turned away by their senseis before they are brought to it — but those who complete it carry the post's mark into the rest of their lives, and the rite of confirmation is performed at the post itself by the school's master in the presence of the Custodian.\n\nThe post cannot be moved. The Ikoma school has at times built training-halls in other cities, and the masters of those halls have asked whether a slip of the original post might be planted in their yards. The Custodians of three generations have refused. The post is the post Tadanari planted, in the earth of the temple where he took his vows, struck by the line of his school for four centuries; what the slip would be would not be the post. The school has accepted the refusal. Replicas of the form's name-plaque are produced by the temple workshop and hung in the daughter-halls, but the post itself stays where it stands.\n\nThe straw wrapping is replaced each spring at the time of the Mending Ceremony common to the temples of Bishamon. The old straw is not discarded; it is burned in a small brazier at the foot of the post, and the ash is mixed back into the packed earth of the alcove. The temple holds that the earth around the post is now as much Tadanari's as the post itself. Strikers who come to the alcove for the hundred-strike practice are asked to remove their sandals before stepping into the square. The earth remembers the feet that have stood upon it."}, {"slug": "naginata-of-the-nun-tomohime", "name": "The Naginata of the Nun Tomohime", "japanese_romaji": "Sugara-no-Naginata", "japanese_kanji": "縋らの薙刀", "fortune": "bishamon", "clan": "lion", "temple": "a temple of Bishamon in Lion lands", "named_entity": "the nun Tomohime (Matsu-born widow who took monastic vows and was twice called to trial-by-arms)", "relic_type": "weapon (naginata)", "description": "A naginata of unusual length — the haft of dark oak rather than the more common ash, the blade longer than a man's forearm and curved more deeply than a soldier's pattern. The blade is set into the haft with a long iron collar bound by braided silk cord, the cord now the color of old straw though it was red when it was first wound. The haft is bare of lacquer; six centuries of hands have darkened it to nearly the color of the iron. The naginata rests horizontally on two cedar pegs against the back wall of a small chamber off the temple's judgment-hall, behind a low rope of plaited rice-straw that pilgrims do not cross.\n\nTomohime was a Matsu woman who had been widowed young, in the late fourth century, and had taken vows at this temple in her twenty-sixth year. She continued to practice the naginata in the temple's training yard as the senior monks permitted, the weapon being honored as a tool of Bishamon even within monastic hands. Twice she was called from the temple by writ of the magistrate to settle matters of dispute by trial-by-arms — both being cases in which the contending samurai had refused all other forms of judgment, and the magistrate had no remaining path. The first trial Tomohime won at the second pass of the blades; the second she won without striking, the contending samurai laying down his weapon when she had taken her stance. Both judgments were accepted, and the matters were settled. Tomohime returned to the temple after each and resumed her vows, asking no honor and refusing the offered stipend. The naginata was hers; on her death it passed to the temple, and the cord was changed once in the century after her death and not since.\n\nA magistrate of the Matsu provinces who cannot resolve a matter by ordinary means — where evidence is exhausted, witnesses have failed, and the contending parties refuse any judgment but combat — may petition the Grand Abbot for the **Calling of the Naginata**. The Grand Abbot in council with the Custodian of Sacred Relics and the Steward of Arms considers the petition; the consideration is rarely brief, and the calling is not given lightly. If granted, a senior monk of the temple is appointed to bear the naginata as Tomohime's successor, and the trial-by-arms is held at the temple's outer training yard rather than in any clan court. The monk fights to Tomohime's standard — sparing where she would have spared, striking where she would have struck — and the result is taken as Bishamon's judgment, mediated through Tomohime's hand.\n\nThe Calling has been performed four times in the six centuries since Tomohime's death. Each calling is recorded in the temple's judgment-roll, with the magistrate's writ, the names of the contending parties, the appointed monk, the outcome, and the disposition of the matter afterward. Three of the four callings ended without a death, the contending party laying down arms before the second pass; the fourth ended in the contending party's death and the matter was settled at the funeral. The records are not consulted in deciding whether a new calling is to be granted, but they are read by the appointed monk before the trial is held — Tomohime's example is the standard.\n\nThe naginata is taken from its pegs only by the appointed monk, on the morning of the trial, in the presence of the Custodian and two senior monks as witnesses. The braided cord is checked for fraying and the iron collar is inspected for slack; if either is found wanting, the calling is postponed and the trial deferred until the temple's smith has put the weapon right. Tomohime would not have fought with a weapon she had not herself prepared. Some appointed monks find the naginata heavier in their hand than they had expected from its size — an auspicious omen, the temple records show, indicating that Tomohime's attention is upon the trial. Some find the weapon balanced as if their own; some find their stance settling into a posture they had not trained, which the senior monks recognize as Tomohime's own and which they do not correct.\n\nThe naginata cannot be carried into ordinary combat. It is a relic of trial, not of war, and to bring it into the field would be to spend Tomohime's judgment on the chaos of battle where no judgment can be heard. The Matsu commanders of the past have at times wished otherwise — particularly during the long campaigns of the present century — and the Grand Abbots have at each request returned the same answer: Tomohime gave her judgments by writ of the magistrate, and the temple will not lend her hand to any other purpose."}, {"slug": "sashimono-of-matsu-kenzou", "name": "The Sashimono of Matsu Kenzou", "japanese_romaji": "Yamaarashi-no-Sashimono", "japanese_kanji": "山嵐の指物", "fortune": "bishamon", "clan": "lion", "temple": "a temple of Bishamon in Lion lands", "named_entity": "Matsu Kenzou (Matsu cavalry commander of the late fourth century, hero of the Pass of White Stones)", "relic_type": "banner (back-banner / sashimono)", "description": "A back-banner of heavy unbleached silk, tall as a kneeling man, mounted on its original lacquered bamboo pole. The field is the ochre-yellow of old Lion campaigns, the mon a single black tiger's claw raked across the silk on a diagonal. The lower third of the banner is dark with the rusted brown of dried blood — Kenzou's own, and the blood of the Matsu cavalry-men who carried his body off the field of White Stones. The pole and banner together rest in a long stone niche behind the main altar of the temple's eastern hall, slanted upright as if planted in the earth.\n\nMatsu Kenzou commanded the second cavalry of the Akodo levy at the Pass of White Stones in the late fourth century, in the war against the Crab raiders who had pressed northward in that lean season. The pass was a narrow defile and the Crab had taken the high ground above it; the Matsu charge that broke them was led by Kenzou with this sashimono on his back, and the men who could not see their captain in the melee followed the banner. Kenzou took three arrows and an axe-stroke before the line broke through. His captains carried him back across the pass on a litter improvised from spear-hafts, the sashimono still on his back because no one would remove it from a man yet living, and he died at the foot of the temple steps four days later. The banner was taken from him by the abbot of the day and given a place in the temple. It has not been washed.\n\nA Lion commander who is to lead a march from the city may petition the Custodian of Sacred Relics for the **Procession of the Pole**. The Custodian carries the sashimono on its pole to the gate of the temple compound at the appointed hour, and the commander and his honor-guard pass beneath it as they file out toward the assembly grounds. Kenzou's spirit attends each procession, and his strength may pass into the line as it crosses the threshold. Soldiers who walk under the pole report the weight of their armor easing for the first li of the march, and some are graced with the smell of horses on the wind though no cavalry rides with them — an auspicious omen, signifying that Kenzou rides at the column's head.\n\nThe Procession is not given for every march. The Custodian and the temple Steward of Arms confer beforehand on whether the campaign merits Kenzou's attention; punitive expeditions, small detachments, and exercises do not. Kenzou was a commander of broken passes and decisive charges, and the temple holds that his interest is on those terms. A commander who insisted on the rite for a lesser work would find Kenzou's attention had not come — though the temple would not say so directly, and the procession would proceed as it always does.\n\nOn the anniversary of the Pass of White Stones, the Custodian performs the **Reading of the Stain**. The banner is lifted from its niche and examined by lamplight; the dark patch on its lower third is studied for any new color the year may have brought. The temple's records, kept for three centuries, note that the stain has sometimes deepened in years of heavy fighting and sometimes faded slightly in years of peace. The Custodian records the year's observation alongside the previous entries and replaces the banner. The pattern across the centuries is read as Kenzou's report on the temper of the times — though Kenzou speaks in his own time, and the report is rarely understood at once.\n\nThe sashimono cannot leave the temple. A captain who marches beneath it carries Kenzou's strength out into the field; the banner itself stays behind so that the next captain may also pass beneath. To carry the banner into battle would be to spend Kenzou's blessing on a single engagement, and the temple has been firm on this point in every generation, even when commanders of high rank have asked."}, {"slug": "war-drum-of-the-ashigaru-tarobei", "name": "The War-Drum of the Ashigaru Tarobei", "japanese_romaji": "Tarobei-no-Taiko", "japanese_kanji": "太郎兵衛の太鼓", "fortune": "bishamon", "clan": "crab", "temple": "a temple of Bishamon in Crab lands", "named_entity": "Tarobei (peasant ashigaru drummer of the Kaiu Wall levy, mid-fifth century)", "relic_type": "implement (war-drum, taiko)", "description": "A medium *odaiko* of cedar staves bound with iron hoops, the drumhead of bull-hide so dark with age it appears black in shadow. The drum is the size of a large rice-cask and stands on a low cedar frame at waist-height, the striking-face turned toward the shrine's outer wall. The hide is patched in four places where it has been struck through; the patches are of paler leather and were sewn in by the drummer's daughter and her descendants, one generation at a time. The shrine is small — three rooms above the inner gate of the Sunda Mizu garrison-outpost — and the drum occupies most of the main room.\n\nTarobei was a peasant ashigaru drummer of the Kaiu Wall levy in the middle of the fifth century. During the long night that the garrison commanders remember as the Breach of the Twelfth Tower, when an oni and its tide of lesser things reached the parapet and the bushi line was broken back from the gate, Tarobei kept his drum at the cadence of the muster though the men around him fell. The ashigaru who could no longer see the line could still hear the drum, and they re-formed on the cadence. Tarobei was killed near dawn — the records do not say how, only that the drum was found upright with its drummer fallen against it, his sticks crossed on the head. The Hiruma captain who took the muster the next morning ordered the drum carried to the gate-shrine and a place made for it there. The Order of Bishamon at Sunda Mizu has tended it since.\n\nThe drum is struck once at dawn and once at dusk every day by the Custodian of the Drum — a Senior Monk who holds no other office and who lives in the shrine itself. The single beat at dawn is for the men who held the Wall the previous night, and the single beat at dusk is for the men who will hold it the coming night. The drum is heard along the parapet for half a li in either direction, and Tarobei's strength may pass into the men of the watch as the beat reaches them. Some on the line are graced with finding their fear quieter for the hour after the beat; others find that the beat lingers in their chest through the long hours of watch and steadies them when the shadow at the foot of the Wall stirs.\n\nWhen the alarm is sounded — the long crooked horns of the garrison taking up the call from one tower to the next — the Custodian of the Drum takes up Tarobei's sticks and beats the **Cadence of the Muster**, the cadence Tarobei himself was beating on the night he died. The cadence is twelve strokes, a pause, four strokes, a pause, twelve strokes, repeated until the bushi line is formed or the alarm is recalled. Ashigaru who hear the cadence and find themselves moving toward their assembly point without thinking are well served by Tarobei; those who freeze in the moment are not abandoned, but Tarobei was a drummer and his gift is to the legs of the running, not the hearts of the still.\n\nThe drum has been struck through four times across the centuries; on each occasion the strike has been heavy enough to split the bull-hide, and on each occasion the strike has been delivered on a night of grave loss along the Wall. The records of the garrison list the four nights: the Breach of the Twelfth Tower itself, the Long Cold of the second century, the Falling of the South Lantern in the fourth, and the Three-Day Watch in the fifth. Tarobei strikes back when his men are dying, and the hide gives. The patches are the daughters' work — Tarobei left a daughter who lived in the garrison village, and his line has tended the patches in each generation since, the labor passing daughter-to-daughter through marriage and adoption alike. When a patch is needed the current daughter is summoned from the village, and the work is hers.\n\nThe drum cannot be moved from the shrine. The garrison commanders of the past have asked whether it might be carried to the Wall itself in time of need, and the abbots of three generations have refused — the drum is heard from the Wall already, and to carry it forward would be to expose it to the kind of stroke that breaks the hide, when the daughters are not always close to hand. Tarobei is content where he is. The Wall stands; the cadence is kept."}, {"slug": "foreign-coin-of-yasuki-tomomichi", "name": "The Foreign Coin of Yasuki Tomomichi", "japanese_romaji": "Ihou-no-Zeni", "japanese_kanji": "異邦の銭", "fortune": "daikoku", "clan": "crab", "temple": "a temple of Daikoku in Crab lands", "named_entity": "Yasuki Tomomichi (Yasuki harbor merchant, sixth century, who broke the Pearl Coast cartel through honest dealing)", "relic_type": "implement (foreign coin in display case)", "description": "A single foreign coin, round, the diameter of a man's thumbnail, struck from what the temple's records describe as \"silver mixed with another metal not known to Rokugani assayers.\" The coin is heavier than it looks, and the metal does not tarnish. On one face is the head of a foreign sovereign, crowned with what may be a sun-disc or may be a coil of flame — opinions among the temple's senior monks differ. On the other face is a single character in a foreign script which no one in living memory has read, though the temple's library holds three separate scholarly attempts at translation. The coin rests on a small velvet cushion within a glass-fronted box of black-lacquered wood, displayed at eye level in a niche off the temple's customs-petitions hall — the hall in which the temple receives the customs officials and merchant-house factors of the Yasuki harbor in their professional capacities.\n\nYasuki Tomomichi was a Yasuki harbor merchant of the sixth century who built his house by breaking the Pearl Coast cartel. The cartel had for two generations fixed the price at which pearls from the southern islands could be landed at the Yasuki Estates, and the Yasuki families who controlled the cartel had grown lazy and grasping. Tomomichi was a younger son of a minor Yasuki line, with no standing in the cartel, and he chose to deal honestly: he paid the southern pearl-divers what they asked, took no kickbacks from his factors, and reported every transaction at the customs post in full. His ships were heckled, his warehouses fired twice, and his factors beaten in the streets. Yet within nine years his house was the largest pearl-trader on the southern coast, and the cartel had collapsed because the divers would deal with no one else. This coin was the first payment Tomomichi ever received from a foreign merchant — a Yobanjin sea-captain who had been refused service by the cartel's houses and who paid Tomomichi in his own people's silver because he had no Rokugani coin to spare. Tomomichi kept the coin to the end of his life and willed it to the temple with a brief note: *let it be displayed where the customs officers may see it.*\n\nWhen a tax dispute, a customs dispute, or a cartel investigation is brought before the Yasuki magistrate's court, the magistrate may petition the Custodian of Sacred Relics for a *witness-of-coin*. The Custodian carries the lacquered box from its niche to the courtroom and sets it on the magistrate's table. The disputants are not required to touch it or address it; the coin sits beside the proceedings as Tomomichi's witness, and the magistrate hears the case knowing that Daikoku — and Tomomichi through him — attends. After the verdict is given, the Custodian returns the coin to its niche, and the magistrate's clerk records in the court log that the coin was present. The temple keeps a parallel log of all such witnessings; the two records are compared each year at the new year audit.\n\nSome petitioners are graced with finding that the coin, when the Custodian unlocks the glass front to confirm its presence at the start of the proceeding, lies with its sovereign-face upward — an auspicious omen that Daikoku looks kindly upon the honest party in the dispute. Some find the coin lying with the foreign-script face upward, which is taken as a sign that the dispute concerns a matter the petitioners have not yet correctly named, and the magistrate is gently counselled to ask further questions before ruling. Some find the coin balanced on its edge against the velvet, which has happened seventeen times in the temple's records, and which is held to be the strongest of the omens — the dispute is one in which both parties have something to confess, and a settlement is to be preferred to a verdict. Most often the coin lies as it was last set down, neither face dominant, and the magistrate proceeds with his own discernment.\n\nThe coin's presence is not the ruling. A magistrate who allowed the omen of the upward face to decide a case, against the weight of evidence and testimony, would be failing his office; the temple is careful to remind new magistrates of this each year. The coin witnesses; the magistrate rules. Yet over four centuries of the practice, the Yasuki court's records show that verdicts in which the coin lay with the sovereign-face upward have been appealed less often than the average, and verdicts in which the coin was edgewise have, with striking regularity, been the cases that later resolved in private settlement before any appeal could be lodged.\n\nThe coin cannot be removed from the temple except in the lacquered box, and even then only under the Custodian's escort, and only to a Yasuki magistrate's courtroom within the Estates. The Yasuki harbor-master has on three occasions over the past century asked that the coin be permitted to travel to subsidiary customs posts up the coast; each request has been refused, with the temple's reasoning recorded in the petition logs: *Tomomichi gave the coin to the central harbor, and to the central harbor it stays.* The lacquered box bears a small brass plaque on its underside, engraved with Tomomichi's family seal and the date of the bequest. The seal is worn smooth in two places, where the Custodians have rested their thumbs each year when carrying the box."}, {"slug": "ledger-of-akodo-tatewaki", "name": "The Ledger of Akodo Tatewaki", "japanese_romaji": "Tatewaki-no-Choubo", "japanese_kanji": "帯刀の帳簿", "fortune": "daikoku", "clan": "lion", "temple": "a temple of Daikoku in Lion lands", "named_entity": "Akodo Tatewaki (Lion treasurer of the Akodo daimyo's house, fourth century, who oversaw the rebuilding of the Akodo treasury after the Plague of the Twelfth Year)", "relic_type": "written material (bookkeeping ledger)", "description": "A heavy bound ledger, the size of a man's spread hand, two fingers thick. The covers are of dark lacquered wood, joined along the spine with stitched silk, and pierced through each cover with a single small hole through which a brass ring passes — the ring is for hanging the ledger on its peg when not in use. The pages within are pale rice-paper, ruled in faint red lines, and the columns are filled in Tatewaki's narrow hand, with the dates of the entries running down the right-hand margin in cinnabar ink. The first page bears the seal of the Akodo daimyo of the fourth century, and beneath it the seal of the Order of Daikoku of the Akodo lands. The ledger rests on a low writing-desk in the temple's treasury-chamber, a small windowless room off the main hall where the temple's own books are kept. It hangs by its ring from a brass peg above the desk when not in use.\n\nAkodo Tatewaki served as treasurer to the Akodo daimyo's house during the long convalescence of the Akodo lands after the Plague of the Twelfth Year, which had hollowed out the domain's revenues for almost a decade. He was given the unwelcome task of telling his daimyo, year after year, how much had been lost and how little remained — and then the still less welcome task of finding, in each successive year, how the domain might survive another. He kept this ledger as his private working-book, in which he set down not only the official accounts but also his own notes on the discrepancies he could not yet explain, the entries he suspected of error, and the corrections he intended to make in the next audit. He wrote in plain language, as a man writes to himself; the ledger has no flourishes and no excuses. After his death in his sixty-ninth year, the ledger was donated to the temple by his eldest son with the request that it be used to guide the audits of those who came after. Eleven generations of Akodo treasurers have consulted it; the Order has not allowed it to be borrowed beyond the chamber in which it rests.\n\nOn the first day of the seventh month — the day on which the Akodo house traditionally closes its annual books for review — the Custodian of Sacred Relics receives the treasurers of the Akodo daimyo's house, of the Order's own treasury, and of any of the great Akodo merchant-houses that wish to petition. Each treasurer brings the ledger upon which they have been working. The Custodian lifts Tatewaki's ledger down from its peg, sets it on the desk beside the petitioner's own book, and opens Tatewaki's ledger to a page at random. The petitioner then reads the page aloud — entries, dates, corrections — and afterward sits with the Custodian for a half-glass of incense, considering whether the page Tatewaki has shown him has any bearing on the work the petitioner has lately been doing.\n\nSome treasurers are graced with a page that addresses the very dispute they have come to resolve — a category of expense Tatewaki had himself misjudged, a creditor he had failed to record until the third audit, a sum that should not have been entered into income at all. They leave the chamber resolved to correct their own books accordingly. Some are graced with a page that bears no relation to their work, and the Custodian counsels them to consider whether some larger pattern has been overlooked — Daikoku's lessons sometimes come slantwise, and the page may speak to a question they have not yet thought to ask. Some are graced with a page upon which the cinnabar of the date is faintly damp to the touch, as though newly inked; this is taken as an auspicious sign that Tatewaki himself has reviewed the petitioner's labor and judged it sound. Most pages are dry, and the petitioner finds in them only what diligence and reflection find together — which is itself the lesson Tatewaki spent his life teaching.\n\nThe ledger does not balance the petitioner's books. A treasurer who has carried an error of a thousand koku into the seventh month will still carry that error out, unless he has noticed it himself in the course of reading Tatewaki's page aloud. Daikoku does not relieve the careful of their care, only joins his hand to theirs. Yet the temple's records show that of the great Akodo accounting scandals of the past four centuries, none have arisen from the books of treasurers who kept their audit-day petitions to the ledger; the men and women who go before Tatewaki each year find errors before errors find them.\n\nThe ledger cannot be removed from the chamber. The Order's workshop produces, on request, *blank books* bound to the same dimensions and with the same cinnabar-ruled paper, into which a treasurer may copy whichever of Tatewaki's pages have spoken to him; many a senior Akodo treasurer's writing-desk holds such a copy beside his own current ledger. The original ledger hangs on its peg, and the brass ring through which the peg passes was bent slightly out of round in Tatewaki's own time. It has not been straightened."}, {"slug": "lucky-mallet-of-high-monk-norikazu", "name": "The Lucky Mallet of High Monk Norikazu", "japanese_romaji": "Uchide-no-Kozuchi", "japanese_kanji": "打出の小槌", "fortune": "daikoku", "clan": "crane", "temple": "a temple of Daikoku in Crane lands", "named_entity": "High Monk Norikazu (Crane monk and founder of an Order of Daikoku in the eighth century)", "relic_type": "implement (mallet)", "description": "A small wooden mallet, the size of a man's fist, carved from a single piece of paulownia wood. The head is squat and weighted, marked along its broad face with the character 福 (*fuku*, \"good fortune\") burned shallow into the grain. The handle is bound in red silk cord, faded now to a pale rose. The mallet rests upon a square of black lacquered wood, set within a shallow brass tray, on a low altar at the front of the temple's petitions hall. Two rice-bales — small, ceremonial, the kind a merchant might carry as a token of good harvest — sit one to each side of the tray.\n\nHigh Monk Norikazu founded the sovereign Order of Daikoku at this temple in the latter half of the eighth century, when the Doji court was opening the city's eastern markets to inland trade and the question of where Daikoku's blessing should rest within the new city had not yet been settled. Norikazu was a third son of a minor Kakita lineage who had renounced his bushi training as a young man and walked to the city with only his teaching robes and this mallet, which had been carved for him by his grandfather, a paulownia-wood craftsman of the southern wards. He used the mallet for forty-one years to strike the daily bell at the small shrine he had been granted on the eastern road. Pilgrims came in such numbers, and the daimyo's favor grew so steadily, that within a generation the shrine had become a temple and the temple a sovereign house. After Norikazu's death the mallet was placed where it now rests, and the bell he had struck for forty-one years was retired beside it.\n\nA merchant who has formed a new venture — a new shop, a new caravan route, a new contract with a domain treasury — may petition the Custodian of Sacred Relics to be received at the mallet's altar. The merchant brings a sample of the goods or coin upon which the venture turns: a measure of rice from the first lot, a length of silk from the first bolt, a string of cash from the first day's takings. The Custodian receives the sample in the brass tray, kneels with the petitioner, and strikes the mallet three times against the black lacquered wood beneath it — once for the merchant's labor, once for the merchant's honest dealings, and once for the favor of Daikoku upon the work. The strokes are soft; the mallet has never been used to strike anything hard, and Norikazu's wishes in this are honored.\n\nSome merchants are graced with a clear ringing in the air after the third stroke — though the mallet strikes wood and not metal, an auspicious sign that Daikoku has heard the petition and that Norikazu joins his teacher's voice to the merchant's. Some are graced with a sudden warmth in the handle's silk binding, which the Custodian also notes; this is taken to mean that the venture's profit will return in kind to the city that hosts it, and the merchant is gently counselled to give generously to the temple's almsgiving box in the years to come. Some are graced with nothing more than the three soft strokes — and even this is a blessing, for Daikoku is not hurried, and many ventures must walk before they may run.\n\nThe mallet's strokes do not produce good fortune in themselves. A merchant whose books are crooked, whose grain is short-weighted, whose laborers go unpaid — Daikoku will not bless such a one, and the strokes of the mallet sound dull and small to those whose hands have not earned the petition. The Custodian does not say so aloud; that is for the merchant's own conscience to know. Yet the temple's records of three centuries show that those who return to give thanks for a venture come most often after the warmth in the silk has been remarked upon, and those who do not return are often those whose ventures the Order has later heard came to grief.\n\nThe mallet may not leave the temple. Daikoku-blessed merchants of the city who travel to open distant markets may petition the temple workshop to commission a *replica mallet* — paulownia, the same red cord, the same shallow-burned character — to carry in their travel-chests. These replicas are common among the senior merchants of the eastern markets, and many a caravan-master will tap his replica thrice against the lid of a treasure-chest before opening it for inspection at a customs post. The original mallet, Norikazu's grandfather's gift, rests on its tray and is struck only by the Custodian, and only at the petition of a merchant who has come in person."}, {"slug": "preserved-rice-bale-of-the-flood-year", "name": "The Preserved Rice-Bale of the Flood Year", "japanese_romaji": "Kouzui-no-Tawara", "japanese_kanji": "洪水の俵", "fortune": "daikoku", "clan": "crane", "temple": "a temple of Daikoku in Crane lands", "named_entity": "Daikoku himself, through the unnamed peasant boy who recovered the bale from the floodwaters of the Great Flood of the Daidoji lowlands", "relic_type": "vessel (rice-bale)", "description": "A single small rice-bale, *tawara*, of the kind a peasant household keeps for the year's own eating — a third of the size of the merchants' standard bale, bound in the older five-cord pattern that has not been the fashion in the Daidoji rice-country for two hundred years. The straw is dark with age, the color of old tea, and the cords are dry but unbroken. The bale rests on a square of pale silk on a low cedar plinth at the rear of the temple's main hall, behind the Daikoku statue and to its right. Twice a year — at the first day of spring planting and the first day of autumn harvest — the bale is lifted by the Custodian of Sacred Relics and weighed on a small bronze balance kept beside the plinth. The weight is recorded in the temple's weighings-book, which now runs to four volumes and is the second-oldest continuous record kept by the Order of Daikoku in Daidoji.\n\nThe bale came to the temple after the Great Flood of the Daidoji lowlands, three hundred and eleven years past. The summer rains had come early and hard, the levees of the lower Daidoji rivers had failed in the third month, and the rice country had been under water for the better part of two months. Whole villages had been swept down to the sea; the survivors had retreated to the high ground and lived on what the Daidoji daimyo of the time could send up from the inland granaries. When the waters finally went down, the rice that had been stored against the planting year had been ruined in almost every storeroom; the Daidoji could not have replanted the lowlands without grain bought at terrible expense from the Akodo, the Yasuki, and even the Yobanjin.\n\nIn the fourth month of the year that followed, a peasant boy of about eleven years — no one took down his name; the temple's records say only *a boy from the village of Higashi-Kawakami, since washed away* — came to the temple carrying this rice-bale on his back. He told the monk at the gate that he had found it caught in the branches of a willow on the far side of the river, a full season after the floods had receded, and that the willow had been bare of leaves when he had last looked at it, but had leafed out in a single day in the night before he found the bale. He had untied the cords and looked inside, and the grain was dry and whole and smelled of the harvest of three years before. He gave the bale to the temple and went home; the monk at the gate did not ask him for the rest of his story. The boy's village was lost to a second flood the following autumn, and the boy with it.\n\nThe first Grand Abbot to study the bale opened its cords and counted the grain. He recorded the count in the first volume of the weighings-book: *grains within, forty-one thousand and three hundred.* The cords were retied. The weighings-book records every formal weighing of the bale since — six hundred and twenty-two weighings in three hundred and eleven years. The weight has varied by less than the width of a finger-bone on the bronze balance across the entire span of the records. The grain has not been counted again. Twice in the temple's history a Grand Abbot has proposed that the cords be reopened and the grain recounted; both proposals were withdrawn before the act, the second time because the Grand Abbot in question had dreamt three nights running of the unnamed boy standing at the foot of his bed and shaking his head.\n\nA peasant or peasant village-headsman of the Daidoji lowlands may petition the Custodian to receive a blessing of harvest at the bale. The Custodian receives such petitions in the season after planting and the season before harvest. The petitioner brings a single grain of the seed-rice that has been set aside for the year's planting, or a single grain of the first cut of the year's harvest, and places it on the silk square beside the bale. The Custodian kneels with the petitioner, recites the temple's standard prayer for abundance, and then sets the petitioner's grain inside one of the bale's outer cords for the night. At dawn the Custodian returns, removes the grain, and gives it back to the petitioner, who carries it home and plants it back into the field or adds it to the household's eating-rice.\n\nSome petitioners are graced with their grain coming back lighter than it went in — a hair's weight only, on the bronze balance, but enough to notice. This is an auspicious omen that the bale has accepted the petitioner's offering and that Daikoku attends the household's harvest. Some find their grain heavier, which is taken to mean that the bale has given of itself to the petitioner's planting, and that the harvest will be richer than the season's signs would predict. Some find their grain unchanged in weight, and this is the most common — the Custodian counsels that the grain was already blessed when it left the field, and that the petitioner has been heard without the need for sign. The temple's weighings-book records the weight-changes faithfully; the totals across each century are very nearly even.\n\nThe bale has not been opened in three centuries. The cords are checked at each weighing for fraying and have shown none; the straw is checked for the small green mold that takes old grain-straw and has shown none of that either. The temple does not assert that the bale will never decay, only that it has not yet decayed. Daikoku is the Fortune of wealth and of the abundance of the rice country, and the bale that came down from the Great Flood is held to be his gift to the Daidoji lowlands — a single bale of true grain in a year when no grain was true.\n\nThe bale cannot leave the temple under any circumstance. The Daidoji daimyo of fifty years past, during a year in which the rice harvest had failed across the southern Crane provinces, asked that the bale be brought to the family granary in solemn procession as a public petition for abundance. The Grand Abbot of that generation refused, and the refusal was upheld by the Doji daimyo when it was appealed to him: *the boy from Higashi-Kawakami brought the bale to the temple, and to the temple it stays.* The temple's workshop produces small woven-straw charms — miniature *tawara* the size of a thumb, blessed at the bale's plinth — which are distributed to the peasant villages of the lowlands each spring and hung over the storeroom doors of their granaries. There are thousands of these charms across the lowlands; there is one bale."}, {"slug": "treasury-key-of-matsu-tameko", "name": "The Treasury Key of Matsu Tameko", "japanese_romaji": "Kura-no-Kagi", "japanese_kanji": "蔵の鍵", "fortune": "daikoku", "clan": "lion", "temple": "a temple of Daikoku in Lion lands", "named_entity": "Matsu Tameko (Matsu daimyo's wife and treasury-keeper of the second century, who defended the family treasury through three lean winters)", "relic_type": "implement (iron key)", "description": "A heavy iron key, longer than a man's hand from the heel of the palm to the tip of the middle finger, with a teardrop-shaped bow at the head and a deep-cut ward at the bit. The iron is dark, worn smooth on the shaft where Tameko's grip lay, and pitted along the bow where the cord that once tied it to her sash has long since been removed. From the bow now passes a length of pale yellow silk, knotted in the simple square knot favored by the Matsu of Tameko's century. The key hangs from a small iron hook driven into the cypress beam that runs above the door of the temple's own treasury-chamber — not displayed, but in active use as the ceremonial second-key for the chamber's lock. The temple's working key is kept by the Steward of the Treasury; Tameko's key is brought down only at the audit-days and the petitions days, and is otherwise left on its hook for any monk passing through the corridor to see.\n\nMatsu Tameko was the wife of the Matsu daimyo of the second century. She was a daughter of a minor Akodo lineage, brought into the Matsu family for political reasons, and her husband had little expectation of her beyond the customary. He was wrong in this. When her husband and the senior officers of the house were called away to a long campaign on the northern marches, Tameko took up the keys of the family treasury at her mother-in-law's insistence and held them for nineteen years, through three lean winters in which the harvest failed in the Matsu provinces and the family treasury was the only line of defense between the peasantry and starvation. She fed the peasants. She fed the garrison. She fed the temples — first the Order of Bishamon, as was proper for a Matsu wife, and then the Order of Daikoku, when the Bishamon abbots themselves wrote to the daimyo on campaign begging him to honor the Daikoku monks as well, since it was Daikoku's wisdom that had kept the treasury from emptying. Tameko's husband returned in her twenty-first year of marriage; she returned the keys to him. She died seven years later, of a wasting illness she did not name to her family. The treasury key — *this* key — she had asked, in her last weeks, to be sent to this Temple of Daikoku, with the request that it never be melted down for its iron.\n\nThe temple has used the key as its own treasury-chamber key ever since, with one ceremonial wrinkle: the working key is kept by the Steward of the Treasury, and Tameko's key is brought down to the lock only at the four audits of the year — first month, fourth month, seventh month, tenth month — and at any petition-day on which a treasurer or monk asks to consult the chamber for guidance. On these occasions the Custodian of Sacred Relics lifts Tameko's key down from its hook, fits it to the lock himself, and opens the chamber with it. The petitioner enters the chamber behind the Custodian; the door is closed; the petition is heard within. The key is returned to its hook when the chamber is closed again.\n\nA Steward of the temple, the Order's senior accountants, or the Matsu daimyo's own treasurers may petition the Custodian to be received at the chamber when a budget dispute or a hard reckoning falls before them. The most frequent petitioners are the temple's own Stewards, who must each year reconcile the Order's income against its obligations — the Daikoku temples of the Matsu domain are responsible for a great web of grain-distributions, vassal-house tithes, and almsgiving disbursements, and the reconciliation is not easy work. The Custodian sits with the petitioner in the chamber for the time of a half-glass of incense, and the petitioner sets out his difficulty aloud while the chamber's records and the strongboxes stand witness. The Custodian does not advise. Tameko advises, through the chamber she now holds.\n\nSome petitioners are graced with the lock turning unusually easily under Tameko's key, an auspicious omen that her hand is upon the reckoning and that the petition has been heard. Some find the lock catching once — a small resistance, easily worked through — which is taken as a sign that one item in the reckoning has not yet been correctly set down, and that the petitioner should review his books for the entry Tameko has flagged. Some find the lock catching twice or more, which the Custodian receives with concern; he closes the chamber, returns the key to its hook, and asks the petitioner to come back another day, after he has examined his work with fresh eyes. Most often the lock turns as locks turn, neither smoothly nor stiffly, and the petition is heard without omen — Daikoku, like Tameko, is not given to flourishes when plain work is what the day requires.\n\nThe key supports the reckoning; it does not perform it. A treasurer who hopes that the lock will turn smoothly enough to relieve him of finding the gap of three hundred koku in his books will be disappointed; if Tameko's hand is upon his work, it is upon his work, and the work is still his. The temple's records of nine centuries show that the Stewards who consult the chamber most often are also the Stewards whose audits run cleanest — though the records do not say, and the temple does not assert, whether the consultation produces the cleanness or only attends it.\n\nThe key cannot be removed from the corridor above the treasury-chamber door. The Matsu daimyo of two generations past, having heard the story of Tameko, asked that the key be brought to the family's annual New Year ceremony at the castle for a single day, that he might honor it in his great-grandmother-by-marriage's name; the Order considered the request for a full season and then declined, with the temple's reasoning recorded in the petition logs: *Tameko gave the key to the temple's treasury, and to the temple's treasury it serves.* The Matsu daimyo accepted the answer without protest, and sent a generous gift of cypress beams the following spring, from which the temple replaced the worn hook above the chamber door."}, {"slug": "twin-sake-flasks-of-akimitsu-and-mariko", "name": "The Twin Sake-Flasks of Akimitsu and Mariko", "japanese_romaji": "Tokkuri-no-Tsui", "japanese_kanji": "徳利の対", "fortune": "daikoku", "clan": "crane", "temple": "a temple of Daikoku in Crane lands", "named_entity": "Akimitsu and Mariko (peasant rice-brewers of the Kakita lowlands, fifth century, whose household prospered into a great Kakita-vassal sake-house)", "relic_type": "pair (sake flasks)", "description": "Two earthenware sake-flasks of the round, round-shouldered shape called *tokkuri*, each the height of a man's hand spread thumb-to-little-finger. One is glazed in pale celadon green, the other in a deeper iron-rust brown; together they sit on a low cedar tray on a side altar in the temple's household-prosperity hall, beneath a hanging scroll on which is painted the character 福 (*fuku*, \"good fortune\") doubled — once in the green of the celadon flask, once in the brown of the iron-rust. A small white porcelain cup rests between the two flasks. The flasks are filled once a year, on the first day of the new year, by the senior brewers of the Kakita-vassal sake-house that descended from the relic's founders; they are emptied each evening by the Custodian, who pours a thimble's worth into the porcelain cup as the day's offering and drinks it himself.\n\nAkimitsu and Mariko were a peasant couple of the Kakita lowlands in the fifth century, rice-brewers in a hamlet two days south of the temple. They married late — both in their thirtieth year — and worked together at the craft Akimitsu had inherited from his uncle: brewing sake from the broken grain that the rice-merchants would not buy, and selling it to the dock-workers of the Kakita river-ports. Their first year of marriage they brewed thirty bottles. Their fifth year, three hundred. Their tenth year, three thousand. They had no children and built their house instead from their work; they brewed in pairs, Akimitsu mixing the rice and Mariko tending the yeast, and the practice in their house was that no batch was ever begun unless they were both present and both sober. When they died — Mariko first, in her seventy-second year, Akimitsu within the same month — the brewery passed to Akimitsu's nephew, who was granted vassal status by the Kakita house in recognition of the brewery's by-then-considerable contribution to the Kakita treasury. The nephew donated the founders' last pair of flasks to the temple, with the prayer that household prosperity be remembered as a thing of *two* hands and not one.\n\nA married couple — newly wed, long-married, or estranged and seeking reconciliation — may petition the Custodian of Sacred Relics to be received at the household-prosperity hall. The Custodian draws a thimble of sake from each flask into the porcelain cup, sets the cup between the petitioners, and asks them to drink — first the wife from one side of the cup, then the husband from the other, finishing the cup between them. They are then asked to speak together, in the Custodian's hearing, one matter of their household upon which they have not yet agreed: a purchase, a sending of a child to study, a debt to be paid, a guest to be received. The Custodian does not advise; he only listens. When the petitioners have spoken what they came to speak, the Custodian bows them out and refills the cup from neither flask, leaving it dry until the next morning.\n\nSome couples are graced with the sake from the green flask tasting clearly sweeter than the sake from the brown — an auspicious omen that the wife's wisdom in the matter is the wisdom Daikoku favors. Some find the brown tasting fuller and rounder, which is taken to mean that the husband's view is to be honored. Some find no difference at all between the two, which is held to be the rarest and finest blessing — Akimitsu and Mariko brewed as one, and a household that drinks as one is a household Daikoku has already prospered. Some find one of the flasks bitter or sour, which the Custodian receives gravely; he counsels the couple to return after the next planting season, and the petition is logged as *deferred* rather than complete.\n\nThe flasks do not produce prosperity from nothing. A household whose accounts are slovenly, whose servants go unpaid, whose lands lie unworked — Daikoku will not gild such a household, and the couple who come petitioning to escape the consequences of their own neglect will find the sake teaches them nothing they did not already know. The temple's records of seven centuries show that couples who return year after year, in good seasons and bad, are the couples whose houses grow steadily — and the temple has long since ceased trying to determine whether the petitioning was the cause or the consequence of the steadiness.\n\nOn the first day of the new year, the flasks are carried in procession from the household-prosperity hall through the temple grounds and out into the surrounding streets, borne by two senior monks beneath a small silk canopy. The procession ends at the gate of the Kakita-vassal sake-house that descended from Akimitsu and Mariko's brewery, where the senior brewers refill the flasks for the coming year and bow the procession back to the temple. Married couples line the procession's route and bow as it passes; those whose households have prospered in the year past leave a single grain of rice on the lacquered tray that one of the junior monks carries before the canopy. The grain is brought back to the temple and added to the next morning's almsgiving bowl.\n\nThe flasks cannot be replaced. The Kakita-vassal sake-house has, twice in seven centuries, sent a master potter to the temple asking permission to replicate the pair for their own household altar; both petitions were refused, with the temple's reasoning that the green and the brown were chosen in Akimitsu and Mariko's own time and are not to be matched by later hands. The temple's workshop produces only the small porcelain cups, which it distributes to newlywed couples of Kakita lineage and to such Kakita-vassal couples as the Custodian deems worthy."}, {"slug": "hammer-of-hida-katsuro", "name": "The Hammer of Hida Katsuro", "japanese_romaji": "Tetsuchi-no-Tsuchi", "japanese_kanji": "鉄槌の槌", "fortune": "ebisu", "clan": "crab", "temple": "a temple of Ebisu in Crab lands", "named_entity": "Hida Katsuro (Hida-vassal smith of the southern foundries, fourth century after the founding of the great Crab castle)", "relic_type": "implement (smith's hammer)", "description": "A long-hafted smith's hammer, the head a single block of forge-blackened iron with a slight asymmetry to its striking face — the right side a touch wider than the left, from the way Katsuro's grip wore the steel over a working lifetime. The haft is oak, darkened with sweat and quenching-oil to the color of old tea. A short hempen cord is tied around the haft just below the head; into the cord is braided a single thread of red, the color of the apron-stripe of the Hida foundry guild. The hammer rests on a pair of iron pegs driven into the wall of a small forge-shrine adjoining the temple's main hall — a working forge with a banked fire kept always alight, and a low altar of unworked stone beside it where the local smiths leave their offerings.\n\nHida Katsuro was a smith of the southern foundries in the fourth century after the great Crab castle's founding. He served the Hida family for forty-one years and is credited in the foundry records with the forging of more than a thousand spear-heads, several hundred plowshares, and the iron banding of three of the great gates of that castle itself. The famous part of his story comes from his thirty-eighth year, when a minor Hida-vassal lord — whose name the temple does not record, for Ebisu does not steady the names of the dishonest — demanded that Katsuro forge a set of executioner's blades for the punishment of his own peasants over an unpaid tax he himself had set in bad weather. Katsuro refused, saying only that his hammer was Ebisu's and would not strike for cruelty. The lord threatened him; Katsuro continued his ordinary work. The lord was eventually overruled by his own father, the matter passed, and Katsuro went on forging plowshares and spear-heads for the Hida bushi until he laid the hammer down in his sixty-third year. He gave it to this Temple of Ebisu in the year of his retirement, and the smiths of the surrounding lands have come to honor it ever since.\n\nOn the first day of the seventh month, when the local foundries bank their fires for the brief monsoon rest, the Custodian of Sacred Relics performs the **Blessing of the Tools**. Smiths and carpenters and stonemasons of the city bring their working hammers, chisels, adzes, and saws to the forge-shrine. The Custodian lifts Katsuro's hammer from its pegs and lays its head once, gently, against the head of each tool brought, while the smith or craftsman states aloud the work the tool is intended for in the coming season. Ebisu, Fortune of honest work, accepts the tool into his sight when its purpose is honest, and a tool so blessed is held to ring true through the season's labor.\n\nSome craftsmen are graced with the brief, clear ring of the iron when Katsuro's hammer touches their tool — an auspicious sign, taken to mean that Ebisu has set his hand upon the work to come. Some are graced with the warmth of the hammer-head against their palm when they bear their tool away, a sign that Katsuro himself has put his weight behind their season. Most experience nothing remarkable, and the blessing is no less for it; the work of the season will be its own witness to Ebisu's regard.\n\nThe Custodian may refuse to bless a tool. This is uncommon, but it happens — perhaps once in each Blessing — when the smith pauses too long in stating the tool's purpose, or when the purpose stated rings false in the Custodian's ear. The Custodian does not give a reason; he sets the hammer back on its pegs and asks the craftsman to return the following season. Ebisu does not steady the hand of the deceitful. The craftsman who is refused is not shamed, but is given to understand that he should reflect on what work he means to do.\n\nA smith who has been commissioned for a single great work of unusual importance — the iron banding of a new gate, the forging of a daimyo's farm-blade, the hammers and chisels for the rebuilding of a damaged temple — may petition the Custodian for a private blessing outside the seasonal ceremony. The smith comes alone with his hammer (or with the first iron of the commission, unfinished), and the Custodian lifts Katsuro's hammer and touches it to the smith's, and the smith speaks his commission aloud. The blessing of an honest commission is given freely. The blessing of a doubtful commission is refused as politely as the seasonal refusals, and as without explanation.\n\nKatsuro's hammer cannot be removed from the forge-shrine. The fire beside it has not gone out in three centuries, and the smiths of the temple keep it banked through every season. Replicas are not made; the hammer is not a tool to be carried, but a witness to which tools are brought. To take Katsuro's hammer from the shrine would be to ask Ebisu to bless work he has not seen, which is not Ebisu's way."}, {"slug": "honest-masu-of-yasuki-bunzo", "name": "The Honest Masu of Yasuki Bunzo", "japanese_romaji": "Makoto-no-Masu", "japanese_kanji": "誠の升", "fortune": "ebisu", "clan": "crab", "temple": "a temple of Ebisu in Crab lands", "named_entity": "Yasuki Bunzo (Hida-vassal rice steward, second century of his domain's establishment)", "relic_type": "implement (rice-measure)", "description": "A simple cedar rice-measure (a *masu*) the size of a fist, hand-carved and unadorned, with one small character — 誠 (*makoto*, \"honesty\") — burned into the inside of one corner. The exterior is the pale color of cedar where the wood is smooth; the interior is darker, oil-soaked from generations of grain. It rests on a low lacquered stand in a side-chamber off the temple's commercial-petitions hall.\n\nThe masu belonged to Yasuki Bunzo, a Hida-vassal rice steward of the local domain in the second century of its establishment. During the famine of his fourteenth year of service, Bunzo was tasked with redistributing the temple's stored grain to the starving villages of the northern provinces. He used this single masu for every measure, and the rice did not run out until every family had received their share. The chamberlain who audited the redistribution afterward could not reconcile the recorded measures with the volume actually distributed; he wrote in his journal that he simply trusted Bunzo, and that Ebisu must have multiplied the grain through his faithful service.\n\nWhen a grain merchant in the surrounding domain is accused of fraud, the County Magistrate may petition the temple for a *measure-test* as one element of his investigation. The merchant brings a sample of his own grain. He pours it into the Honest Masu in the presence of the Custodian of Sacred Relics, levels it with a flat strike-stick cut from Bunzo's staff, and the result is observed. Ebisu, Fortune of honest work, steadies the hand of the righteous and refuses to steady the hand of the deceitful. A merchant whose conscience is clear pours calmly and levels the grain on the first stroke; a merchant whose conscience is heavy finds the grain piling unevenly, the strike-stick catching, the measure refusing to settle.\n\nThe test is not a verdict. The magistrate weighs the result alongside the merchant's account books, the testimony of his neighbors, and the records of his prior dealings. Some magistrates make a point of demanding the test from both parties in a commercial dispute, knowing that a calm conscience steadies the hand and a guilty one shakes it — and that Ebisu's hand is upon the room either way. The magistrate's discernment, supported by what the relic reveals about each party's standing with Ebisu, is what produces the ruling.\n\nThe masu has not measurably warped in its centuries of service. The character 誠 in its corner was burned in by Bunzo's own hand without flint or fire — Ebisu blessed the wood so that it smoldered to mark him. The strike-stick is one of seven cut from cedars of Ebisu shrines, rotated through use; the temple's records do not identify which is the original, and this is as Ebisu wills, for what matters is the work and not the tool.\n\nThe masu cannot be removed from the temple. Traveling tax officials carry blessed *replicas* commissioned from the temple workshop, but the original Bunzo-masu has not left the temple in living memory. To lose it would be a grievous offense to Bunzo's spirit and to the long tradition of honest measure he sustains in the local lands."}, {"slug": "net-of-yasuki-rokuemon", "name": "The Net of Yasuki Rokuemon", "japanese_romaji": "Manjiki-no-Ami", "japanese_kanji": "満食の網", "fortune": "ebisu", "clan": "crab", "temple": "a temple of Ebisu in Crab lands", "named_entity": "Yasuki Rokuemon (Yasuki-vassal fisherman of the coastal hamlets, second century of the Yasuki domain)", "relic_type": "implement (fishing net)", "description": "A small drag-net of woven hemp cord, the size that a single fisherman would cast from the stern of a flat-bottomed coast-boat. The cord has gone the dark color of old rope, soaked through with sea-salt and fish-oil over generations. The leaden weights along its bottom edge are river-stone rather than lead — Rokuemon's village was too poor for metal in his time, and he tied each stone himself with a fisherman's knot, the knots still visible after these centuries. The net is folded carefully into a low square of unvarnished pine wood, lined with rice-straw, and rests on a stone plinth in a side-chamber of the temple that opens onto the harbor through a wooden lattice. The sound of the tide can be heard from the chamber at all hours.\n\nYasuki Rokuemon was a fisherman of one of the small coastal hamlets that pay rice and fish to the Yasuki domain, in the second century after the domain's founding. He was a tenant of no particular distinction until the famine year that the temple records simply as *the Hungry Spring* — the year a late frost killed the rice-shoots in their flooded paddies up and down the coast, and the inland granaries were already depleted from a hard winter. While the headsmen of the inland villages petitioned the Yasuki for relief, Rokuemon and the fishermen of his hamlet rowed out every morning, in every weather, and brought back what they could. Rokuemon's catch in that spring was such that no household in three hamlets went without a fish-meal, and his own family ate last of all. The boats of the other fishermen often came home empty; Rokuemon's net came home heavy. He gave away the bulk of his catch to the temple's almsgiving station and to the headsmen of the inland hamlets, and asked no payment. He fished for thirty-six years after that spring and was buried in a fisherman's plain shroud, and the net was brought to the temple by his eldest son.\n\nA fisherman preparing for a voyage of difficulty — a long passage down the coast, a season of unfavorable winds, the first voyage of a new boat — may petition the *Shika*, the Knower of Guests, to be received at the chamber of the Net. The Shika opens the pine box, lifts a single corner of the net between his two hands, and lays it briefly against the shoulder of the fisherman in the manner of a blessing. The fisherman speaks aloud his voyage and the hold he hopes to fill, and the names of the household whose meals depend on the catch. The Shika folds the corner back into the box and closes the lid. Ebisu, Fortune of honest work, lays his regard upon the fishermen whose work is done in honest measure, and Rokuemon's net is the witness through which the regard is given.\n\nSome fishermen are graced with the smell of fresh sea-water rising from the net when the Shika lifts it — an auspicious omen, signifying that Rokuemon has put his hand upon the voyage to come. Some are graced with a single drop of water falling from the net to the stone floor though the net has been folded dry for weeks, a sign that the catch will be full. Most experience nothing remarkable, and the blessing is no lesser for it; a fisherman who has honestly prepared his boat and his nets and his crew has already done the work that Ebisu favors, and the relic does not undo what the fisherman has not done.\n\nOn the first morning after the spring equinox, the Shika performs the **Telling of the Knots**. He kneels before the box, unfolds the net to its full extent in the chamber, and counts the stones along the bottom edge — the same one hundred and eighty-seven river-stones Rokuemon tied to it in his thirty-first year. Each year one or two of the knots are found a little loosened by the season's handling, and the Shika ties them again with the original cord. The count is set down in the chamber's register beside the count of the year before, and the temple's records of nine generations show that the count has never changed. Rokuemon tied his knots once and well, and the stones do not fall.\n\nA fisherman who has lost his boat — to storm, to gaijin raiders along the Yasuki coast, to fire — may petition the Custodian of Sacred Relics for a piece of cord cut from a *replica net* woven by the temple's monks each spring. The cord is tied around the wrist or the rope-belt and is carried until the next boat is launched, when it is tied to the mast. The replica nets are not the Net of Rokuemon; they are blessed at the Net's box and given freely, and the fishermen of the Yasuki coast carry them without ceremony, the way a man carries a coin in his sleeve.\n\nThe original net cannot be removed from the chamber. The harbor below has come to expect its presence; the Shika of the present generation has heard from the harbor-master that the older fishermen will not put to sea on a morning when the chamber's lattice is closed. The temple does not close the lattice. To take the net out to a boat would be to ask Ebisu to bless a single voyage rather than the whole work of the coast, which is not Rokuemon's gift to give."}, {"slug": "sandals-of-the-walking-monk-tessen", "name": "The Sandals of the Walking Monk Tessen", "japanese_romaji": "Tessen-no-Waraji", "japanese_kanji": "鉄旋の草鞋", "fortune": "ebisu", "clan": "dragon", "temple": "a temple of Ebisu in Dragon lands", "named_entity": "Tessen (mendicant monk of the Mirumoto roads, four generations past, who walked the same circuit for forty-one years)", "relic_type": "garment (straw sandals)", "description": "A pair of straw sandals — *waraji* — the kind that any peasant or traveling monk wears for a day or two and then replaces. These are not replaced. They sit side by side on a low cypress shelf at the entrance of the temple's traveler-hall, where pilgrims leave their own sandals before entering the inner rooms. The straw of the original weave is so worn down that the soles are barely a finger's thickness in places; the cord ties are frayed but knotted, and the rear loop of the left sandal has been mended once, in coarser straw than the original. Above the shelf hangs a small wooden plaque painted with the character 旋 (*sen*, \"circuit, turning\") — the second character of the walking monk's name.\n\nTessen was a mendicant of the Order of Ebisu who came to this temple in the year of its rebuilding, four generations past. He did not present himself as a teacher and he never accepted the rank of Senior Monk, though he was offered it twice. Instead, with the Grand Abbot's blessing, he walked. Every morning at first light he set out from the temple along the eastern road that climbs through the Mirumoto foothills, visiting in turn the seven hamlets along the road as far as the watchtower at the *Three Pines Pass*, and every evening he returned by the western branch, visiting the four hamlets along the river. He carried a beggar's bowl and a small bundle, and what he was given by one hamlet he distributed in the next. He spoke with peasants in their fields, helped repair their tools when his hands were able, witnessed births, prayed at the bedsides of the dying, and walked. He walked the same circuit for forty-one years. When the soles of his sandals wore through, he wove himself new ones at the temple's straw-shed; when his hands grew too stiff to weave, the temple's novices wove them for him. He died on the road between the third and fourth hamlets of the eastern arm, in his sixty-ninth year, in the company of a peasant family who had set down their planting to walk the last hour with him. The peasants brought his body back to the temple, and the sandals he had been wearing were placed on the shelf at the traveler-hall entrance. They have not been moved.\n\nThe temple's circuit has been walked by a successor monk every day since. The Custodian of Sacred Relics — for the Order of Ebisu in the Dragon lands, as in other clans, keeps the title — appoints the *Walker of the Circuit* from among the monks who have completed their second year of vows. The appointment is a quiet honor; the Walker carries no special markings and earns no special rank from the work. Each morning the Walker bows at the shelf, dons his own ordinary sandals, takes up a beggar's bowl and a bundle, and sets out along Tessen's eastern road. He returns by Tessen's western branch in the evening, having visited the same eleven hamlets, having spoken with whatever peasants and travelers wish to be spoken with, having given out what was given to him in the hamlet before. Ebisu, Fortune of honest work, walks the circuit beside the Walker; the work itself is the offering, and the sandals on the shelf are the witness that the offering has been continuous.\n\nA pilgrim arriving at the temple may leave a single coin, a handful of rice, a folded sleeve-cloth, or any small thing in the bowl that rests on the shelf below the sandals. The Walker of the day takes the offering into his bundle and gives it out along the circuit. Some pilgrims are graced, when they place the offering, with the faint smell of road-dust rising from the old straw — an auspicious omen, signifying that Tessen accepts the offering personally and that the gift will reach a particular hamlet where it is needed. Some are graced with the brief sound of footfalls on the cypress floor when no monk is near, a sign that Tessen walks beside the day's Walker. Most pilgrims experience nothing remarkable, and the offering is no less for it; Ebisu's care for the eleven hamlets does not depend on the pilgrim's sign.\n\nA young monk of the Order who has begun to suspect that the labor of the road exceeds his patience may petition the Custodian to be permitted to kneel for a single afternoon at the shelf. The Custodian permits this without ceremony. The monk kneels, the sandals rest before him, and the monk considers the forty-one years. Some monks rise and ask to be appointed to the next available Walker's turn. Some monks rise and ask to be released from their vows, and the Custodian grants the release without rebuke — Ebisu's labor is not for every hand, and a monk who cannot walk the road honestly is better laboring elsewhere. The shelf is a teacher whose lesson is given without speech.\n\nOn the first morning after the autumn equinox, the Custodian performs the **Counting of the Hamlets**. He walks the circuit himself, in Tessen's manner, and at each of the eleven hamlets he asks the headsman whether the year's circuit has been faithful — whether the Walker has come daily, whether the gifts have arrived, whether any sickness or distress went unwitnessed. The headsmen of the eleven hamlets have answered yes in every count for four generations. This is the Counting's quiet glory, and the Custodian sets the year's answer down in the register beside the years before.\n\nThe sandals cannot be moved from the shelf. The shelf cannot be moved from the traveler-hall entrance. The straw-shed at the back of the temple weaves replacement *waraji* for each Walker as they wear out their own; the temple gives these out also to pilgrims who ask, blessed but otherwise unremarkable, and the pilgrims wear them home along whatever road is theirs. The original sandals do not walk again. They have walked enough."}, {"slug": "shuttle-of-mirumoto-ohatsu", "name": "The Shuttle of Mirumoto Ohatsu", "japanese_romaji": "Hata-no-Hi", "japanese_kanji": "機の梭", "fortune": "ebisu", "clan": "dragon", "temple": "a temple of Ebisu in Dragon lands", "named_entity": "Mirumoto Ohatsu (Mirumoto-vassal weaver of the Kitsuki river-towns, fifth century after the founding of the Kitsuki line)", "relic_type": "implement (weaver's shuttle)", "description": "A weaver's shuttle of close-grained mountain-cherry wood, the length of a woman's hand from wrist to fingertip and the breadth of two fingers. The wood has been polished to a soft glow by the passage of warp-thread and the oil of generations of palms; the carved channel for the bobbin is darkened where the silk has worn it. Along one side of the shuttle a single line of small characters has been incised by a thin blade — Ohatsu's own counting-marks for the bolts she finished in her last winter, seventeen marks in all. The shuttle rests on a folded square of unbleached hemp cloth, on a low table at the side of the temple's craftsman-petitions chamber. On the wall above hangs a single bolt of plain cotton, woven by Ohatsu herself in the autumn of her sixty-second year and given to the temple when she could no longer sit at the loom.\n\nMirumoto Ohatsu was a weaver of one of the river-towns that pay cloth and dye to the Kitsuki family, in the fifth century after the Kitsuki line's founding. She was a tenant weaver of no great household, and would have passed without record but for the long winter of her sixty-second year, when the Kitsuki river-towns were cut off from the cotton-merchants of the south by an early snow and the dye-houses had no work. The peasants of three towns came into that winter with patched and threadbare clothing, and the new season's bolts had not arrived. Ohatsu, who had given up most of her weaving by then on account of stiffening hands, set up her loom again. She wove every day from dawn to second-bell, on the cotton thread the temple still had in store from the previous summer, in the plain undyed weave that her mother had taught her. She finished seventeen full bolts that winter, and the temple's almsgiving steward distributed them to the village headsmen for cutting and patching. No family of the three towns went into spring in rags. She died the following autumn, at the loom, having woven the eighteenth bolt to within a hand's-breadth of completion. Her shuttle was placed beside the unfinished bolt and brought together to the temple.\n\nA craftsman of any trade — weaver, carpenter, smith, dyer, paper-maker, cooper — who has been commissioned for a work of particular weight, may petition the Custodian of Sacred Relics for the **Blessing of the Shuttle**. The craftsman brings the first material of the commission: the cut warp-thread for a weaver, the first stave for a cooper, the unworked iron for a smith, the prepared mulberry pulp for a paper-maker. The Custodian receives the craftsman in the chamber, lifts Ohatsu's shuttle in his right hand, and passes it once — slowly, in the manner of a weaver throwing across the warp — above the material the craftsman has brought. The craftsman names the commission aloud, names the household or temple for whom the work is being done, and names the season by which the work must be completed. The Custodian sets the shuttle back upon its cloth and bows; the craftsman bows in turn and carries the material home.\n\nSome craftsmen are graced with the soft sound of a loom — the brief, clear thump of a beater settling a weft against the warp — when the shuttle passes above their material. This is taken to mean that Ohatsu has accepted the commission into her sight, and is an auspicious omen that the work will rise from the craftsman's hands without crooked seam. Some are graced with the warmth of their material when they take it back into their hands, a sign that Ohatsu has set her labor beside theirs. Most craftsmen experience nothing remarkable, and the blessing is no lesser for it; Ebisu, Fortune of honest work, knows the craftsman by his work and not by the omen at the chamber.\n\nThe Custodian may refuse a blessing. This is uncommon, perhaps two or three times a year, when the craftsman names the commission in a way that the Custodian's ear judges to be incomplete — when the season named is impossible, when the household named has commissioned another craftsman already without releasing the first, when the materials brought are not the materials that the commission would require. The Custodian sets the shuttle back without passing it over the material, and asks the craftsman to return when the commission has been clarified. Ebisu does not bless a work whose terms the worker has not honestly stated.\n\nA craftsman whose commission has gone badly — a bolt that has unraveled, a barrel that leaks, a blade that has cracked at the tang — may return to the chamber for the **Counsel of the Shuttle**. The Custodian receives the craftsman with no rebuke, lifts the shuttle, and asks the craftsman to speak each step of the work from the beginning. The shuttle is not passed over anything; it rests in the Custodian's hand while the craftsman speaks. Some craftsmen, in the speaking, find the fault themselves, and bow and leave to begin again; the shuttle's witness has been enough. Some are still uncertain at the end of the telling, and the Custodian sits with them in silence for as long as the craftsman wishes. Ohatsu's last winter is in the wood of the shuttle, and the craftsman who sits with it for a while is rarely without counsel by the end.\n\nOn the first day of the tenth month, when the dye-houses of the Kitsuki river-towns prepare for the winter's indigo work, the Custodian performs the **Reading of the Marks**. He kneels before the table, lifts the shuttle, and reads aloud the seventeen counting-marks Ohatsu cut into it in her last winter — one for each bolt she finished. The reading is short. The Custodian sets the shuttle back down and gives the day's blessing to the gathered weavers and dyers of the town, who have come in their work-aprons to witness. The Reading does not change from year to year, and the marks do not fade.\n\nThe shuttle cannot be removed from the chamber. The temple's workshop will, on request, weave a small **token-cloth** of plain undyed cotton in Ohatsu's weave — a square the size of a man's palm, woven on the shuttle of one of the senior weavers of the temple and blessed at Ohatsu's table before being given. Craftsmen of the river-towns keep these token-cloths folded in their tool-chests; some keep them tied around the handle of a favored tool. The original shuttle does not leave its hemp cloth, for Ohatsu's labor is not borrowed — it is honored where it lies, by being remembered."}, {"slug": "wayfarers-bowl-of-old-bunsuke", "name": "The Wayfarer's Bowl of Old Bunsuke", "japanese_romaji": "Tabibito-no-Wan", "japanese_kanji": "旅人の椀", "fortune": "ebisu", "clan": "any", "temple": "a temple of Ebisu, in any city of the Empire", "named_entity": "Bunsuke (peasant farmer of a small village, three generations past)", "relic_type": "vessel (rice-bowl)", "description": "A simple wood-turned rice bowl, unglazed and undecorated, the diameter of a man's palm. The exterior is the pale color of natural wood; the interior is darker, stained by forty years of rice. A tiny chip on the rim of the foot — exactly the size of a single grain of rice — marks the spot where Bunsuke's wife dropped the bowl on the day of their wedding. It rests on a low table at the temple's almsgiving station, beside the threshold where the daily charity meal is distributed.\n\nBunsuke was a peasant farmer in a village three generations past. He was a poor tenant farmer with three children, but for forty years every wandering monk, ronin, beggar, or pilgrim who passed through his village received a bowl of rice from his wife at this exact bowl. Bunsuke held that feeding the homeless and the religious was the highest duty of an Ebisu-blessed peasant — that the Fortune of honest work expected its faithful to share the fruits of that work. After he and his wife died (within the same week, in their late seventies), the bowl was found clean and dry on a shelf in their hut. The village headsman donated it to the temple, where the Custodian of that generation said only: \"this is a great relic; place it where it can continue its work.\"\n\nThere is no formal ritual. A pilgrim or visitor may leave a single grain of rice in the bowl. Each evening, the *Shika* — the Knower of Guests, the Steward of Hospitality in the temple's archaic Sangō tradition — empties the bowl and uses the rice in the next morning's charity meal for the poor of the surrounding city. The bowl is a perpetual almsgiving circuit, mediating between pilgrims who wish to honor Ebisu and the poor of the city who need to eat. Bunsuke's spirit oversees the circuit personally — the grain a pilgrim leaves is the same grain, multiplied many times through the seasons, that fills the bowls of the city's hungry.\n\nSome pilgrims are graced with finding the bowl warm to the touch when they leave their grain — an auspicious omen, signifying that Bunsuke has accepted the offering and that Ebisu's favor follows the pilgrim into the coming season. Some are graced with the smell of cooked rice in the alcove though no fire burns there, a sign that the grain has already been blessed for the meal it will become. Most pilgrims experience nothing remarkable, and the gift itself is its own blessing whether or not the pilgrim is granted further sign.\n\nOn the first day of each month, the Shika performs the **Counting of the Grains**, a ritual observation kept since the bowl came to the temple. He counts the grains placed in the bowl by pilgrims during the preceding day, then marks one grain with a single stroke of black ink. The bowl is left undisturbed overnight in the sealed alcove. At dawn the Shika returns and counts again, and seeks the marked grain. The records of three generations of Shikas show that sometimes the count is higher than the day's offerings, sometimes equal, sometimes lower; sometimes the marked grain is found, sometimes it has gone into the bowl's blessing and cannot be recovered, sometimes it appears the next month after the count had recorded it lost. Each pattern is interpreted in light of the season, the festivals nearby, and the alignment of the pilgrims of that day. Bunsuke's spirit has its own rhythms, and the Counting is a way of attending to them rather than testing them.\n\nThe bowl cannot be removed from the almsgiving station; the daily charity circuit depends on it, and the poor of three nearby wards have come to expect the meal. To destroy the bowl would break Bunsuke's continuing gift to the city's poor, which Ebisu would not forgive."}, {"slug": "antler-of-the-stag-of-mercy", "name": "The Antler of the Stag of Mercy", "japanese_romaji": "Jihi-no-Tsuno", "japanese_kanji": "慈悲の角", "fortune": "fukurokujin", "clan": "any", "temple": "a temple of Fukurokujin, in any city of the Empire", "named_entity": "Fukurokujin himself, by way of a stag the Fortune is said to have ridden in the founding age", "relic_type": "natural object (antler shed, mounted on dark wood)", "description": "A single shed antler of a great red stag, nearly the length of a man's arm, with five points. It is mounted on a polished slab of dark wood — the wood is plain, not lacquered, and the antler is held by two small bronze brackets that grip it loosely enough that it could be lifted off without effort. The slab rests on a low altar of pale stone in the temple's antechamber, the room that any visitor must pass through before reaching the inner hall. A single oil lamp burns on the altar at all hours. The antler itself is the color of old ivory along its main beam, darker at the points where the stag would have rubbed it against trees in the season before shedding.\n\nThe antler is held to have been shed by the stag upon which Fukurokujin rode in the founding age, when the Fortune walked among the magistrates of the early Empire and instructed them in the difference between justice and harshness. The stag, by the temple's account, shed its antlers each spring as ordinary stags do, and one spring left this antler in a clearing in the mountains east of Otosan Uchi. The antler was found by a charcoal-burner who recognized it, by the unusual length and the five points, as no ordinary stag's, and brought it to the temple then being built. This was nearly a thousand years past. The antler has been the temple's foundational relic ever since.\n\nThe temple at Otosan Uchi is small by the standards of the Imperial capital, but its standing is great because of its proximity to the Imperial Board of Justice. Senior magistrates of the Board — Emerald magistrates returning from the provinces with difficult reports, junior judges newly appointed and uncertain, magistrates summoned to argue particularly contested cases — make a point of passing through the antechamber before they enter the Board's halls. By long custom an Imperial magistrate touches the antler with the fingertips of his right hand as he passes, lightly, the way a man might brush a doorframe. The touch is brief, the gesture nearly invisible. The Custodian of Sacred Relics, who sits in the antechamber during the hours the Board is in session, notes who has passed and who has not, but does not speak of it.\n\nFukurokujin grants wisdom to the magistrate who acknowledges that he is about to rule on the lives of men, and grants mercy to the magistrate who acknowledges that he himself may have erred. The touch of the antler is the acknowledgment in physical form. Some magistrates are graced with a sudden coolness at the fingertips, as though the antler had given back a measure of the warmth a worried hand carries — and these magistrates often find, by their own account, that a small detail of the case they had been overlooking comes clear to them as they cross the threshold into the Board's chamber. Some are graced with the lamp on the altar flickering as they pass, an auspicious omen that Fukurokujin walks with them into the chamber. Most touch the antler and feel only the cool of old bone, and proceed about their business, and this is the gift the antler usually gives — the reminder that they are passing from one room to another.\n\nThe antler is also brought into the Board's chamber on the rare occasion when a *case of mercy* is to be heard — that is, a case in which a sentence already passed is being reconsidered on petition, whether of the family of the condemned or of the magistrate who passed the sentence and has begun to doubt it. On these days the Custodian carries the antler in his two hands, walking before the senior magistrate, and lays it on the chamber's central table for the duration of the hearing. The bronze brackets remain at the temple; the antler is set directly on the wood, on a small white silk cloth. Two of the petitioning Board's magistrates of the past century have written privately that they could not have brought themselves to commute a sentence without the antler before them on the table. One wrote that he could not have brought himself to uphold a sentence, either, without it. Fukurokujin's mercy is not soft; it is the mercy that sees clearly and rules accordingly.\n\nThe antler does not regrow what it has lost; a stag's antler, once shed, is finished. The Custodian shows the antler to junior monks each year on the festival of Fukurokujin and reminds them that the Fortune's wisdom is the wisdom of what has been let go, not of what is still being grasped. The five points of the antler are taken, by the Order's teachings, to be the five questions a magistrate must ask before he rules — but the temple does not write the questions down, holding instead that each magistrate must arrive at them in his own life, and that to fix them in writing would be to fail Fukurokujin's lesson.\n\nThe antler may not be carried beyond the walls of the temple precinct, save in the Custodian's hands and for a session of the Board. Junior monks who wish to make pilgrimage to the temple from the provinces are received with hospitality and may touch the antler once before leaving; some take home small carved tokens of stag-antler from the temple workshop, cut from the antlers of ordinary deer offered to the temple by hunters of the surrounding hills, blessed at the altar before being given. The original antler has rested in its brackets for nearly a thousand years. It has not yellowed nor cracked. The temple does not say why."}, {"slug": "book-of-judgments-of-shinjo-haruna", "name": "The Book of Judgments of Shinjo Haruna", "japanese_romaji": "Onjou-no-Sho", "japanese_kanji": "温情の書", "fortune": "fukurokujin", "clan": "unicorn", "temple": "a temple of Fukurokujin in Unicorn lands", "named_entity": "Shinjo Haruna (Unicorn provincial judge of the fourth century, called the Bending Judge)", "relic_type": "written material (bound book of rulings)", "description": "A heavy book bound in dark calfskin, the size of a man's two hands placed side by side, its pages of thick rice-paper inked in a careful but unornamented hand. The cover is unmarked except for a single character — 温 (*on*, \"warmth\" or \"tenderness\") — pressed into the leather with a hot iron. The book rests open on a slanted reading-stand of pale wood in the temple's magistrate-petition hall, beside a low cushion where the petitioner kneels. A small brass paperweight, cast in the shape of a sleeping fawn, holds the open pages flat. The page is turned once each morning by the Custodian of Sacred Relics, in order; the book is read through completely once each year, beginning at the spring equinox.\n\nShinjo Haruna was a provincial judge of the Unicorn lands in the fourth century, in the time when the lineages were still settling the disputes that had arisen from the Return. She was called the Bending Judge by those who came before her, because she was known to find the place where the strict reading of the law would have produced an outcome that no decent person could uphold, and there to bend. She bent only at that place, and not before it; her rulings on clear cases were as exact as any judge's. But she had a particular gift for the case where the letter of the law and the spirit of mercy pulled in opposite directions, and for finding the ruling that honored both. She wrote each of her significant judgments into this book over the forty-one years of her service, in her own hand, with a brief summary of the case, the strict reading, her ruling, and — most importantly — the reasoning by which she had arrived at the bending. There are three hundred and seventeen entries. When she died at seventy-three, the book was given to the Temple of Fukurokujin, which had blessed her appointment in her youth.\n\nA magistrate facing a case in which the law's strict application would produce a result that troubles his conscience may petition the Custodian for a consultation. The petitioner kneels at the reading-stand and speaks the shape of his case aloud in three or four sentences: the facts, the strict reading, his hesitation. The Custodian then turns the brass fawn aside and turns the book to a fresh page — not chosen, but the page where the morning's turning has brought the reader, or, if the petition comes in the afternoon, the page the morning had just opened. The petitioner reads the entry that lies before him, slowly, twice if he wishes.\n\nFukurokujin's wisdom and mercy come together in Haruna's hand. Some petitioners find an entry that addresses a case so closely resembling their own that the path of bending is plain to them, and they leave the hall already at peace with the ruling they will write. Some find an entry quite different from their case in its facts, and the Custodian asks them to consider what Haruna's reasoning, not her ruling, suggests for the matter at hand — for the book is consulted for *how to think*, not for what to decide. Some find an entry in which Haruna refused to bend, and these petitioners are often the ones who go home and uphold the strict reading, having recognized that their case is not one where mercy is owed. Some find no clear guidance, and the Custodian sends them home with the counsel that they must rule by their own discernment, and that Fukurokujin grants wisdom to those who do not lean too heavily on the wisdom of others.\n\nThe book also serves a second use, observed by the Custodians of three centuries. A magistrate who has already issued a ruling, and who has been troubled afterward by doubts as to whether he ruled justly, may petition for a *retrospective consultation*. He kneels and reads the day's entry without speaking his case first. Some are graced with an entry that vindicates them in their own conscience, and they leave their doubts at the reading-stand. Some are graced with an entry that gently rebukes them, and these petitioners often arrange, in private, some quiet act of restitution to the wronged party — a gift, a recommendation, a delayed favor — that cannot undo the ruling but softens it. The book does not record what was read or what followed. The Custodian, who sees the rulings come and go but does not know what the petitioner has read in any given session, does not comment.\n\nThe book is consulted by the County Magistrate of Shinjo Province in advance of any capital case. By long custom the magistrate's first ruling on a young magistrate's first capital case is also read aloud before the book, with the young magistrate seated at the cushion — Haruna having herself written that no judge should pass sentence of death before the age of thirty-three without the counsel of an older voice, and that her own book might serve as that voice when no older judge was within riding distance.\n\nThe book is not allowed to leave the hall. The Custodian, who is by tradition a former magistrate herself, will accompany a senior judge to a particularly grave trial elsewhere in Shinjo lands once or twice in a generation, carrying instead a *traveling volume* — a slim companion book containing fifteen of Haruna's most consulted entries, copied by senior monks, bound in calf, and blessed at the reading-stand before it leaves. The original book has been read through ninety-six times by the temple's reckoning. The leather is supple, the pages unworn at their edges, and the ink as dark as the day Haruna laid down her brush. Fukurokujin's hand is upon the book, and the book is upon the magistrates of the Shinjo, and the magistrates are upon the people, and the people, in their many small mercies, are upon Fukurokujin."}, {"slug": "bronze-mirror-of-isawa-katsumi", "name": "The Bronze Mirror of Isawa Katsumi", "japanese_romaji": "Chie-no-Kagami", "japanese_kanji": "知恵の鏡", "fortune": "fukurokujin", "clan": "phoenix", "temple": "a temple of Fukurokujin in Phoenix lands", "named_entity": "Isawa Katsumi (Isawa scholar-shugenja, sixth century, master of the Library of Two Doors)", "relic_type": "implement (bronze hand-mirror)", "description": "A bronze hand-mirror the size of a man's palm, with a short handle wrapped in old silk cord. The polished face is darkened with age to the color of an autumn river at dusk; a viewer's reflection is visible, but softened, the features blurred at their edges. The back of the mirror is cast with a low relief of a stag drinking from a forest pool, the antlers extending past the rim of the disc. The mirror rests on a small folded square of pale silk on a low writing-desk in a side study off the temple's main scriptorium, where a single oil lamp is kept burning during the hours when the library is open.\n\nIsawa Katsumi was the master of the Library of Two Doors during the long winter of the sixth century, when the great snows kept the Phoenix scholars at their books for nine months together and the disputes among them grew bitter. She was famed in her age not for any single treatise — she wrote only one, on the proper ordering of commentaries, and even that she left unsigned — but for being able to enter a room of quarreling shugenja and, by quiet questions, send each of them back to their desks no longer certain of their own argument. Her students said of her that she did not teach what to think but how to be uncertain. She kept this mirror on her writing-desk and consulted it before answering any difficult question. When a student of hers, frustrated, demanded to know what she saw in the mirror that the rest of them did not, she said only: \"the face of someone who does not yet know.\"\n\nA scholar who has come to a place in his study where he can no longer see his way forward — a senior monk whose commentary has lost its thread, a young initiate whose memorization has begun to harden into mere recitation, an Isawa shugenja whose theological argument has begun to bend toward a conclusion he is no longer certain he believes — may petition the Custodian of Sacred Relics for a session with the mirror. The Custodian unlocks the study, lights an additional lamp, and seats the petitioner before the writing-desk. The petitioner places his current work — the page he cannot finish, the passage he cannot interpret — on the desk before him. He then takes up the mirror and looks at his own face for the length of one slow breath, and sets it down.\n\nFukurokujin's wisdom is given to those who can hold their own ignorance steadily. The bronze does not show the petitioner anything beyond his own face; what the petitioner is asked to do is look at the face of the one who is stuck, and recognize that face as his own. Some are graced with a clear thought arriving in the moment they set the mirror down — an angle they had not considered, a question they had not asked. Some are graced with the mirror's reflection seeming, for a moment, to belong to someone slightly older than themselves, as though Katsumi were lending the petitioner her own eyes for the length of the breath. Some see only themselves and find no insight, and the Custodian sends them back to their books with the counsel that Fukurokujin's gift is sometimes a longer patience and not a faster answer.\n\nThe mirror is consulted in a quieter way during the *Audit of Commentaries*, held twice each year in the weeks before the snows close and after they open. The senior monks of the scriptorium gather at the writing-desk in turn, each bringing the work of the past season, and each looks once into the mirror before reading aloud what he has written. The audit is not a test of doctrinal correctness; it is a check upon the writer's clarity of mind. A senior monk who finds, after the mirror, that he cannot read his own passage without flinching is permitted to withdraw the passage from the season's record without explanation. Three withdrawals in a single audit are taken as Fukurokujin's signal that the monk should pass to a different task for a time, and the Custodian arranges it without comment.\n\nThe bronze has not lost its sheen, though it has not been polished within recorded memory. The silk cord on the handle has been replaced perhaps twelve times across the centuries; the temple's records mark only that each replacement was performed by a senior monk who had himself completed an Audit of Commentaries without withdrawal. The folded silk square beneath the mirror is changed each spring at the time of the Mending Ceremony. The mirror itself does not leave the writing-desk.\n\nA scholar leaving the Library of Two Doors at the end of his career may petition for a *replica mirror* from the temple workshop — a smaller hand-mirror of polished brass, cast with the same stag-and-pool on its back, blessed at the writing-desk by the Custodian before being given. These replicas are kept on the writing-desks of senior scholars in Phoenix lands and beyond. They are not the relic; what they remind the bearer of is the discipline of looking once at his own face before answering a hard question."}, {"slug": "mirror-pool-of-old-otsuyu", "name": "The Mirror-Pool of Old Otsuyu", "japanese_romaji": "Otsuyu-no-Ike", "japanese_kanji": "お露の池", "fortune": "fukurokujin", "clan": "unicorn", "temple": "a temple of Fukurokujin in Unicorn lands", "named_entity": "Otsuyu (peasant woman of Yoki-mura, six generations past, whose counsel the village headsmen would seek)", "relic_type": "natural object (small stone basin holding a still pool of rainwater)", "description": "A small basin of dark river-stone, the width of a man's two hands, set into the floor of a covered alcove at the back of the temple's modest courtyard. The basin holds rainwater that the alcove's overhanging roof collects and slowly feeds in through a copper channel; the water is changed by the rains rather than by any human hand, and the level rises and falls with the seasons. The water is always still. The stone of the basin is smooth, worn dark by water and by the hands of generations of women who have knelt beside it. A wooden bench sits before the basin, just wide enough for two to sit together. The alcove is open at the front and screened from the wind on three sides.\n\nOtsuyu was a peasant woman of Yoki-mura, a market town in the Iuchi Province six generations past. She was the wife of a tenant farmer, the mother of seven children, and the grandmother in time of nineteen more. She had no learning beyond the household and the rice paddy; she had never been outside the province and could read only the few characters needed for the village's accounts. But her counsel was sought, over the fifty years of her motherhood, by every other woman in Yoki-mura who could not work out what to do with a willful son, a daughter caught in folly, a husband grown cold, an in-law turned cruel. She kept this basin in the courtyard of her own farmhouse, fed by the eaves, and she would seat the visitor on a bench beside it and speak with her at length. The villagers said of Otsuyu that she did not give advice; she asked questions, and listened, and asked more questions, and by the end the visitor had usually answered her own question and gone home knowing what to do. Otsuyu credited the basin. *\"I look at the water,\"* she would say, *\"and the water shows me what to ask.\"*\n\nWhen she died at seventy-eight, the village headsman of that generation prevailed upon her sons to give the basin to the small Temple of Fukurokujin that had grown up in the town's market quarter. The basin was installed in the alcove where it now sits, and the eaves were extended to feed it as the eaves of her farmhouse had. The temple's senior monk of that generation, a woman herself, said only that Fukurokujin's mercy is also the mercy of a wise neighbor, and that the basin had been a temple in its own right before it ever came to one.\n\nA mother whose child has begun to go wrong — a son turning to drink, a daughter refusing the match her family has arranged, a younger child whose troubles the mother cannot name — may petition the Custodian of Sacred Relics for a *sitting with Otsuyu*. The Custodian, who is by long custom a married woman or a widow of the town, walks the petitioner to the alcove, seats herself on one end of the bench, and asks the petitioner to sit on the other. She does not speak first. The petitioner speaks the trouble; the Custodian listens, and looks at the water; and after a while she asks a question. The petitioner answers; the Custodian asks another question. The water is between them.\n\nSome petitioners are graced with seeing, in the surface of the pool, a faint reflection of an older woman beside their own — Otsuyu sitting where the Custodian sits, lending her face to the listening. Some are graced with the surface of the pool stirring once, of itself, in the moment when the right question has been asked, the moment when the petitioner understands at last what her child needs of her. Some see only their own reflection, doubled by the bench, and find their answer regardless; Otsuyu's gift in life was that she asked the questions a mother had not let herself ask, and the gift survives her in the asking, with or without omen.\n\nThe basin is also sat at by families who have come to a difficult choice that affects all of them — whether to send a younger son to a temple rather than to the fields, whether to refuse a marriage proposal that brings money but estranges the family from a beloved aunt, whether to forgive a runaway daughter who has returned with a child not her husband's. The Custodian seats them all on a long bench brought into the alcove for the purpose. The same protocol holds: she does not speak first; she asks questions in turn; the water sits between them. Decisions reached at the basin are by long custom not announced for three days afterward, so that the family may live with the decision before committing it; many decisions soften in those three days, and the Custodian holds that this softening is itself Fukurokujin's mercy at work.\n\nA magistrate too may sit at the basin, though this is rarer; the temple is a small one and the County Magistrate of Iuchi Province sits elsewhere. But on the occasion when a magistrate has been called to rule on a family matter — a disputed adoption, an inheritance contested between siblings — and the law gives him no clear answer, he may come to Yoki-mura and sit with the Custodian as any mother would. The Custodian treats him no differently. The water is between them.\n\nThe basin's pool has never been emptied by human hand, nor has the temple's record-keepers found a season in which the rains failed it entirely. Twice in living memory the pool has gone very low, but did not dry; the Custodian of those years interpreted the low water as Fukurokujin's signal that the town's mothers were carrying heavier burdens than the basin alone could ease, and arranged for additional alms-rice to be distributed through the women's quarter for the season. The water rose with the next rains. The temple does not say what the connection was.\n\nThe basin cannot be moved; the alcove was built around it, and to lift it from its setting would be to abandon Otsuyu's gift. The temple workshop produces small *companion bowls* of dark stone, the size of a cupped hand, blessed at the basin and given to married daughters leaving Yoki-mura for households elsewhere. The companion bowls are filled with rainwater by the daughters and kept on shelves in their new kitchens, and consulted in their own private sittings when the daughters become mothers in their turn. Many a household in the Iuchi Province keeps such a bowl. The water in them does not stay clear for long, but the women who keep them do not mind; what they look at is not the water but the bowl, and the bowl reminds them of the kind of question to ask."}, {"slug": "staff-and-scroll-of-high-monk-jion", "name": "The Staff and Scroll of High Monk Jion", "japanese_romaji": "Jion-no-Tsue", "japanese_kanji": "慈恩の杖", "fortune": "fukurokujin", "clan": "fox", "temple": "a temple of Fukurokujin in Fox lands", "named_entity": "High Monk Jion (Fox monk three centuries past, famed for road-mercy)", "relic_type": "implement (staff with attached scroll)", "description": "A walking staff and an attached scroll, mounted upright against the back of an old wooden chair in a side chamber of the temple, beside a small altar where seven candles are kept lit at all times.\n\nThe staff is cut from the heart of a cedar that grew in the deep wood of Kitsune Mori, near the spring where the Vermillion Threshold Stones are first marked each spring. The wood is dark with age and the oil of generations of hands. Its top is bound with hempen cord around an iron ring, from which depends a short cord and a brass loop. Through the brass loop is tied the scroll — a long roll of rice-paper, blackened along its edges, the calligraphy within in Jion's own careful hand.\n\nThe chair against which the staff rests is small and plain, the size that an old man would sit in. The cushion is replaced each spring at the time of the Mending Ceremony; the rest of the chair has not been touched since Jion himself sat in it.\n\nThe scroll contains High Monk Jion's writings on mercy — meditations he composed during the forty years he served as High Monk of this temple. The writings are not theological treatises but observations: cases he had heard, judgments he had made, refusals he had given, doubts he had carried, and the wisdom Fukurokujin had granted him by the end of each. Jion was famous in his own age for walking the Imperial Roads through Kitsune Mori with his staff and granting clemency to bandits who had repented and to travelers wrongly marked by the wood's wardings. The Kitsune family of his generation did not always agree with his judgments, but they did not contest them; even the most exacting of the road-rangers acknowledged that mercy and justice are both Fortunes' gifts, and Fukurokujin's hand is upon mercy.\n\nA pilgrim who has been marked by the forest — whose footprints have begun to show as fox-paw, who hears barking at night, who has dreamed of fur — may petition the Shika to be received at the chamber of the Staff. So too may a pilgrim who has not been marked but knows themselves to have done wrong, and seeks to understand whether mercy is available to them.\n\nThe Custodian of Sacred Relics — for the Order of Fukurokujin keeps that title as the senior officer beneath the High Monk — receives the pilgrim, kneels with them before the staff, and asks them to speak their burden in three sentences. The pilgrim speaks. The Custodian then unrolls a portion of the scroll and reads aloud the passage that lies in front of them. The portion is not chosen; the scroll is unrolled to whatever length the pilgrim's hand has indicated when they touched the brass loop, and the passage that lies before the reader's eyes is the passage given.\n\nSome pilgrims hear a passage that addresses their burden directly, in words so apt they cannot speak for some moments afterward, and the Custodian then waits with them in silence. Some hear a passage about a case quite unlike their own, and the Custodian asks them to consider how it might apply — Fukurokujin's wisdom is sometimes given as a riddle. Some hear a passage that seems to refuse them, and the Custodian sends them home with the counsel that they should return when their understanding has deepened. Some are graced, in addition, with a faint trembling in the staff against the chair, an auspicious omen that Jion himself has heard the burden and judges it worthy of his successors' attention.\n\nThe mercy of Fukurokujin is not a release from consequence. A bandit who comes to the chamber with sincere repentance may receive a passage that points him to the act of restitution he must perform — to seek out those he wronged, to labor for them, to surrender himself to the County Magistrate. The forest's wardings, the Kitsune family's instruments, do not lift on their own. But a pilgrim who has performed the act the scroll required of him is, after some seasons have passed, permitted to walk the Imperial Road again — and the rangers, in case after case, have found that his prints are his own.\n\nThe staff and scroll cannot leave the temple. The Kitsune family of the present generation, with whom the Order has at times disagreed, has never asked for the staff to travel; what could be said by the staff in motion is said better by Fukurokujin's monks remaining in place, with pilgrims coming to them. The temple's workshop produces small *replica scrolls* for those who wish to take a portion of Jion's wisdom home — excerpts copied by senior monks and blessed at the chair before being sent out, taken home and kept on writing-desks, or carried in sleeve-pockets, or read aloud at family altars. The original scroll does not unroll for itself, and does not leave its loop."}, {"slug": "unfinished-treatise-of-shiba-mochizuke", "name": "The Unfinished Treatise of Shiba Mochizuke", "japanese_romaji": "Mikan-no-Sho", "japanese_kanji": "未完の書", "fortune": "fukurokujin", "clan": "phoenix", "temple": "a temple of Fukurokujin in Phoenix lands", "named_entity": "Shiba Mochizuke (Phoenix Master of Mercy, eighth century, who renounced his seat after the famine ruling)", "relic_type": "written material (unfinished bound manuscript)", "description": "A bound manuscript of sixty-three pages, sewn in the simple Phoenix fashion with pale blue thread, the cover plain dark cloth. The interior pages are filled in a fluent, hurried hand with the dense calligraphy of a scholar writing rapidly toward a conclusion he can see and is racing to reach. The seventeenth page from the back is the last written page. The remaining pages — sixteen of them — are blank. The manuscript rests in a shallow open box of pale wood on a low table in a side chamber off the temple's library, beside a small inkstone and a single brush that have not been used in three centuries. The brush is dry; the inkstone is dry.\n\nShiba Mochizuke was a Phoenix Master of the eighth century, one of the senior advisors to the Shiba daimyo of his generation, and the holder of the lineage's traditional seat on the question of mercy in famine. In the third year of the long famine that struck the western Phoenix provinces, the daimyo asked his Masters to rule on whether the lineage's grain reserves — held against the threat of war with the Lion — should be opened to the starving peasantry. Mochizuke had been arguing for opening the reserves for two years, against the other Masters, who held that the reserves were the lineage's protection and could not be touched. The daimyo, finally, ruled with Mochizuke. The reserves were opened. The peasants were fed. And in the next spring, no war came, and the famine eased, and the lineage was praised throughout the Phoenix lands for the wisdom of its mercy.\n\nMochizuke renounced his seat that summer. He left the daimyo's court, came to this Temple of Fukurokujin, and asked to be received as an ordinary monk. The temple received him. The reason he gave, in the only public statement of his renunciation, was that he had been right to argue for the opening of the reserves, but that he had been right for the wrong reason — that he had argued from compassion for the peasants, but that his deeper motive had been the desire to prove the other Masters wrong, and that this motive, undetected by him for two years, had nearly led him to argue too vehemently to be heard. *\"I won the ruling,\"* he wrote in the only line of his renunciation that has been preserved, *\"and I do not know whether I was the right person to win it.\"*\n\nHe spent the remaining nineteen years of his life as a monk of the temple. In his last decade he began this manuscript — a treatise, never titled, on the difference between a mercy that arises from the love of others and a mercy that arises from the love of being seen as merciful. He wrote in spurts, between his daily duties, and the manuscript grew. He intended, by all accounts of his attendants, to finish it. He died one evening in his sleep with the manuscript open on the table beside him and the brush still wet. The attendant who found him in the morning recorded only that the brush was on the inkstone where Mochizuke had laid it down, and that the page open before him was the seventeenth from the back. The temple's senior monks of that generation conferred, and decided that the treatise should remain as it was: unfinished, with the inkstone and brush as Mochizuke had left them.\n\nA samurai who has issued an order he has come to regret — an officer whose command sent men into a place from which they did not return, a magistrate who has passed a sentence he has begun to doubt, an administrator whose policy has hurt those it was meant to help, a Master of any school who has won an argument and cannot afterward shake the suspicion that he won it for the wrong reasons — may petition the Custodian of Sacred Relics for an *evening with the treatise*. The Custodian unlocks the side chamber at sunset, seats the petitioner before the open box, and leaves. The petitioner is alone with the manuscript until the temple bell rings for the close of the evening prayers. He may read as much or as little of the manuscript as he wishes. He may not write in it.\n\nThe treatise speaks plainly. Mochizuke wrote without disguise, naming the famine ruling, naming his motive, examining his own argument with the same exactness he had once turned upon the arguments of his rivals. Some petitioners are graced with a passage that addresses the precise question they have come carrying, and they leave the chamber having understood themselves better than they did at sunset. Some are graced with the manuscript opening to the blank pages and not to the written ones — the box is shallow and the manuscript shifts on its own as the petitioner kneels, and some find the blank pages turned uppermost. The Custodian, when this happens, asks the petitioner upon his departure whether he found his answer in the blank pages, and the answer is often yes; Fukurokujin's mercy is sometimes the gift of *not* receiving Mochizuke's words but being asked to write one's own. Some find only the written pages, and read, and leave. Most petitioners read for an hour and emerge quieter than they entered.\n\nFukurokujin's wisdom is not the wisdom of being right; it is the wisdom of knowing why one wished to be right. Mochizuke's treatise, unfinished, instructs by what it does not say as much as by what it does — for Mochizuke himself never reached the conclusion he was racing toward, and the temple holds that this is no defect but the lesson. The samurai who comes to the chamber seeking the answer to his regret will not find a verdict written there; he will find an examination, and he will be invited to continue it in his own life.\n\nThe manuscript may not be copied in full. Senior monks of the Order have for centuries copied individual passages — never more than two pages from any one petitioner's session — into small *companion books* that the temple workshop binds in pale cloth and gives to departing petitioners who have asked. The blank pages are never copied; what is blank in the relic must remain blank in the copy. The original manuscript stays in its open box, beside the dry brush and dry inkstone, in the side chamber off the library. Three centuries of dust have been brushed away by the Custodians; the manuscript itself has not yellowed beyond the warm cream it was when Mochizuke laid down his brush, and the ink is as black as a Master's regret."}, {"slug": "beggars-bowl-of-togashi-daikatsu", "name": "The Beggar's Bowl of Togashi Daikatsu", "japanese_romaji": "Daikatsu-no-Hachi", "japanese_kanji": "大喝の鉢", "fortune": "hotei", "clan": "dragon", "temple": "a temple of Hotei in Dragon lands", "named_entity": "Togashi Daikatsu (founder of a Hotei temple, an ise-zumi who walked as a beggar for forty years)", "relic_type": "vessel (iron alms-bowl)", "description": "A black iron alms-bowl the size of two cupped hands, beaten rather than cast, the iron pitted and uneven across its outer face. The inside is dark-glazed from forty years of rice, broth, and rainwater. Along the lip on one side is a shallow notch worn smooth where Daikatsu's thumb rested against it — the angle and depth of the notch fit a man's right hand, and pilgrims who hold the bowl correctly find their thumb falling naturally into the place. The bowl bears no inscription, no mark of maker, no decoration of any kind. It rests on a square of unbleached linen on a low cypress shelf in a small unadorned hall near the temple's western gate, the hall through which the Children's Festival procession passes each spring.\n\nTogashi Daikatsu was the founder of this Temple of Hotei, in an age before the surrounding settlement had grown to its present size. He was an *ise-zumi* — a tattooed monk of the Togashi house — who in his early years had received the dragon-tattoos and trained in the mountain disciplines of the order. In his thirty-second year, in circumstances the temple does not record (Daikatsu himself, late in life, declined to explain them, saying only that \"the mountain showed me what a man weighs and what he carries\"), he walked down from the mountain in a single under-robe with this iron bowl and a wooden staff. He did not return to the order's main hall. He walked the roads of the Dragon lands, and afterward of the Phoenix lands, and finally of the Lion lands and back again, for forty years, accepting only what was placed in the bowl. He spoke little. He laughed often, and his laugh was loud and surprising — those who heard it once at a roadside fire remembered it for the rest of their lives, and several of the temple's earliest patrons came to the order because of it. In his seventy-third year he returned, set the bowl on a flat stone at the western edge of the pilgrim-settlement, sat down beside it, and announced that this would be the site of a temple to Hotei. He died the same winter. The temple was built around the flat stone, and the bowl was placed on the shelf where it now rests.\n\nIn ordinary days the bowl receives no offerings. Pilgrims may stand before it, kneel before it, leave a single grain of rice on the linen beside it (never inside it), and depart. The hall is open by day and closed only on the three festival days of summer; the Custodian of Sacred Relics passes through it twice a day to ensure that the linen is clean and that no one has placed a coin in the bowl. Coins placed in the bowl are removed and donated to the temple's school for poor children; the donor's name is not recorded. Daikatsu refused coins in his lifetime, accepting only food and water, but the temple acknowledges that pilgrims may not have rice with them, and the children are grateful.\n\nOn the third day of the third month, at the climax of the Children's Festival, the **Procession of the Empty Bowl** carries the iron bowl through the city streets from the western gate to the eastern, and back. The Custodian of Sacred Relics walks at the head of the procession bearing the bowl with both hands. Behind him walk the children of the temple's school, then the children of the pilgrim-city's families, then any monk who wishes to join. The bowl is held with its mouth open to the sky. As the procession passes, the families of the city come out and place into the bowl what they would give to a beggar — a grain of rice, a piece of dried fruit, a small coin, a folded paper crane, a wooden charm. By the time the procession reaches the eastern gate the bowl is heaped to overflowing, and the children carry baskets behind it for the contents that no longer fit.\n\nWhat is collected on the procession is distributed at the eastern gate to the beggars of the city — and the city has many beggars, for it is a place of pilgrimage and pilgrims sometimes arrive impoverished and sometimes leave the same way. Daikatsu's spirit walks the procession alongside the Custodian; some children are graced with seeing an old monk in patched robes walking beside the bowl, smiling at them. Some adults are graced with their offering, once placed in the bowl, settling with a soft chime as of a small bell, though no bell hangs near it. Some are graced with their offering returning to them the same evening in unexpected form — a piece of rice given in the morning found that night on their threshold in twice the quantity, or a coin given that morning replaced by the gift of a neighbor returning a long-forgotten debt. The temple does not promise this; it is the kind of thing Hotei does when pleased.\n\nA monk in late life — a senior monk or higher who is approaching their fifty-fifth year or the end of their active service — may petition the Grand Abbot for the **Forty-Day Walking**. The petitioner walks for forty days on the roads of the Dragon lands with the iron bowl in their hands, accepting only what is placed in it, sleeping under hedges and in temple courtyards, returning each day's offering to the bowl until it is shared with whoever else needs it. The walking is permitted only once in a monk's life. It is not penitential and does not earn rank; it is what it is. Few monks complete the walking without returning early, and the temple does not regard early return as failure — Daikatsu himself, in his early decades of walking, came back to the mountain three times before the walking became permanent. The bowl knows its own pace.\n\nThe bowl cannot be replicated for sale or for gift. The temple workshop produces no copies of any kind; iron bowls in the city markets that claim to be \"after Daikatsu's bowl\" are not blessed and the temple does not contest them, for to contest them would be to claim more for the original than Daikatsu would have claimed. The bowl cannot be removed from the temple except for the Procession and the Forty-Day Walking. In the present century the bowl has gone out only sixty-three times by procession and four times by walking. It has come back each time."}, {"slug": "garden-rake-of-isawa-sumire", "name": "The Garden Rake of Isawa Sumire", "japanese_romaji": "Sumire-no-Kumade", "japanese_kanji": "菫の熊手", "fortune": "hotei", "clan": "phoenix", "temple": "a temple of Hotei in Phoenix lands", "named_entity": "Isawa Sumire (Isawa scholar of the late fourth century, who burned her library and became a gardener at the temple)", "relic_type": "implement (bamboo garden rake)", "description": "A long bamboo-handled rake with a head of fifteen split-bamboo teeth, the bindings of waxed hempen cord. The bamboo of the handle has been polished smooth by hands; the teeth are slightly uneven in length, three of them shorter than the others where they have been replaced over the centuries. The rake is kept upright in a slim wooden rack at the threshold of the temple's gravel garden, beside the worn flat stone where the rake's user removes their sandals. The garden itself is a long rectangle of white river-gravel raked into slow curves around five standing stones, enclosed by a low wall of weathered cedar. From a small bench inside the threshold one can sit and watch the garden without entering it.\n\nIsawa Sumire was an Isawa scholar of the late fourth century, born into a lineage of fire-shugenja and educated, from her sixth year, in the Isawa libraries. By her thirtieth year she had become the senior cataloguer of one of the great libraries — a position of considerable standing, held by appointment of the Council of Elemental Masters. In her forty-fourth year she fell into a long illness from which she emerged thin and quiet. She returned to her library, looked at the seventeen years of marginal notes she had written in her cataloguing journals, and felt nothing. She walked home, sealed the journals into a cedar chest, took the chest into her family's garden, and burned it. The fire took three days to reduce the journals to ash; Sumire sat with the fire the whole time, sleeping in short stretches against the garden wall, taking water and a little rice from her servants. When the ash was cool she scattered it under the persimmon tree, walked to this Temple of Hotei, and asked to be permitted to work in the gardens. She did not return to her lineage. She did not write again. She lived another thirty-six years in the temple, raking gravel and tending the persimmons, and her only known utterances during this time were short observations about the weather and the gravel — none of which were recorded, for she had specifically asked that none be.\n\nThe rake was Sumire's own working tool from her tenth year at the temple until her death. The Custodian of Sacred Relics in the year after her death moved the rake from the gardeners' shed into a place of honor, replaced its leather grip with a finer cord, and instituted the protocol by which it has been used ever since.\n\nA pilgrim who struggles with attachment — to a book they cannot finish, to a position they cannot let go, to a grudge they have nursed beyond its season, to a love that was not returned — may petition the Steward of Hospitality, the *Shika* of the temple's archaic Sangō tradition, for the **Hour of Raking**. The Shika receives the pilgrim at the threshold of the gravel garden, hands them Sumire's rake, and instructs them only: *\"Rake until the bell.\"* The temple's hour-bell is sounded an hour later. The pilgrim enters the garden, removes their sandals, and rakes the gravel for the hour. The patterns to be raked are not specified; some pilgrims attempt to restore the curves they found, some draw new shapes, some rake the gravel flat. When the bell sounds, the pilgrim returns the rake to its rack and leaves by the side gate.\n\nSumire's hand guides the hands of the troubled. Some pilgrims are graced with a single, simple thought arriving in the middle of the hour — the answer to a question they had not consciously asked, the name of the attachment they had not been able to name. Some find that they have, without noticing, raked the gravel into the shape of a character — most often 捨 (*sute*, \"to discard\") or 任 (*nin*, \"to entrust\") — and the Shika, when this happens, permits them to leave the character standing for the day. Some find that they have raked the garden into perfect emptiness, and weep at the threshold; the Shika brings them tea. Most pilgrims simply rake for an hour and leave with their breathing slower than when they came, and this is Hotei's customary kindness. The garden is raked smooth by the next day's first pilgrim, who finds whatever the previous one left and decides what to do with it.\n\nA samurai of any rank may petition for the Hour of Raking; a peasant may also petition, and the temple does not turn away peasants who come barefoot. The fee for the petition is one stone the size of a fist, brought from the pilgrim's home and added to a low cairn outside the garden wall. The cairn is a hundred and fifty years tall and has become a small hill against the wall. Sumire did not begin the cairn; it began of itself, after her death, when pilgrims started bringing the stones unbidden, and the Custodian of that generation decided not to refuse what Hotei was clearly arranging.\n\nThe rake cannot be removed from the temple. Its teeth are replaced as they wear out, three of fifteen having been replaced in the present generation; the Custodian's office does not record which teeth are original, as Sumire herself often replaced her own teeth without ceremony. The handle and the binding cord have not been replaced. The temple workshop produces miniature *replica rakes* of cedar wood, the size of a writing-brush, which scholars and bureaucrats keep on their desks; these are not used to rake anything, but rather are looked at when the work has become too heavy, and Sumire is said to watch over the small lookings as well as the great rakings."}, {"slug": "laughing-fan-of-kakita-shibu", "name": "The Laughing Fan of Kakita Shibu", "japanese_romaji": "Warai-Ougi", "japanese_kanji": "笑い扇", "fortune": "hotei", "clan": "crane", "temple": "a temple of Hotei in Crane lands", "named_entity": "Kakita Shibu (iaijutsu prodigy of the Kakita Academy, late fifth century, who renounced the duel)", "relic_type": "implement (folding fan)", "description": "A simple folding fan of bamboo and unbleached *washi* paper, twelve ribs, the standard size of a Kakita teaching fan. On its broad face is painted a single character — 樂 (*raku*, \"ease, joy\") — in soft black ink. The brushwork is hesitant in places, the strokes uneven; Shibu painted the character with his off-hand, three days after he laid down his sword. The fan rests on a wooden display stand in a small alcove off the temple's main contemplation hall, beside a low window that looks out onto a moss garden.\n\nKakita Shibu was a young iaijutsu prodigy of the Kakita Academy in the late fifth century. He won every duel he entered from the age of fourteen onward; by his twenty-second year he had become a chief instructor and was being considered for appointment as personal champion to the Doji daimyo. On the morning of the duel that would have sealed his elevation, Shibu sat with his father — an old Kakita sensei — and shared tea. His father asked him: *\"What will you do tomorrow?\"* Shibu said: *\"I will duel and win.\"* His father asked: *\"And the day after?\"* *\"I will become the daimyo's champion.\"* *\"And the day after that?\"* Shibu found he had no answer — only that the day after, and the day after that, was a path he could see perfectly and did not wish to walk. He did not appear for the duel. He left his sword at his father's house. He walked the half-day to the local Temple of Hotei, then a modest temple of no great repute, and asked to be made a monk. He took only the fan that had been his teaching aid in the Academy.\n\nThe scandal of Shibu's refusal was great, but he never explained himself further. He spent the remaining fifty-three years of his life teaching village children to read and write in the hamlets nearby, laughing freely, and never accepted a position above novice within the temple. His fan he kept, but used only to cool himself in the heat — never to teach iaijutsu, never to settle a dispute, never as a courtly gesture. After his death the fan was placed on the display where it now rests, and the temple slowly grew in standing as pilgrims came to know the story.\n\nA pilgrim weary of striving — a failed courtier, an aging duelist, a samurai who has lost their place or been demoted, a monk who has begun to suspect their ambitions exceed their wisdom — may petition the Custodian of Sacred Relics to hold the fan for one breath. The Custodian opens the alcove, places the fan in the pilgrim's hand, and asks the pilgrim to breathe once with the fan in their grip. The fan is then returned to its rest. Hotei's wisdom is not given to grasping; the briefest contact is enough.\n\nThe breath of contact reveals what the pilgrim has been refusing to see. Some are graced with a soft chuckle from somewhere in the alcove — Hotei's laugh, an auspicious omen that the pilgrim's renunciation will be accepted with mercy. Some are graced with a single clear thought about what they must lay down to find peace, and they leave the temple already at peace. Some weep without knowing why, and this is Hotei's particular kindness — the burden was greater than they had let themselves know. Most pilgrims feel only the bamboo and the breath, and even this is no failure; Hotei is content to be unhurried with souls.\n\nThose who try to hold the fan longer than a breath — and a handful do, every generation, samurai of strong will who think they may extract more from the relic — find that the fan is not in their hand when they look. It rests on its stand as before. The Custodian does not comment on this, nor punish the attempt; Hotei has already spoken by withholding what was not asked for properly.\n\nThe fan has not yellowed in three centuries. The character 樂 is as soft and uneven as the day Shibu painted it. The bamboo ribs are the same bamboo, though the *washi* paper has been replaced perhaps twice over the centuries — the Custodians of the past did not record the dates of the replacements, for such records would suggest a relic that is *made* rather than *given*.\n\nThe fan cannot be removed from the temple. Kakita who wish to honor Shibu's example may petition the Custodian to commission a *replica fan* from the temple's workshop, painted with the same character by a senior monk; the replicas are taken home and placed on writing desks or kept in sleeve-pockets, but the original fan does not leave its alcove. It is not a teaching aid. It is a witness."}, {"slug": "patch-cloth-sack-of-mirumoto-hayato", "name": "The Patch-Cloth Sack of Mirumoto Hayato", "japanese_romaji": "Tsugihagi-no-Fukuro", "japanese_kanji": "継ぎ接ぎの袋", "fortune": "hotei", "clan": "dragon", "temple": "a temple of Hotei in Dragon lands", "named_entity": "Mirumoto Hayato (retired Mirumoto general of the early sixth century, who laid down his banners and walked to the temple)", "relic_type": "vessel (cloth sack of small charms)", "description": "A worn cloth sack the size of a man's two cupped hands, sewn from forty-one squares of fabric in differing colors and weaves — some indigo cotton, some pale silk, some coarse hempen weave, some patterned in the old Mirumoto sword-and-claw design now faded almost beyond reading. The squares are stitched together with thick linen thread, the seams uneven, the patches not arranged by color or pattern but by no order at all. The sack closes with a simple drawstring of plaited silk. Inside it, on a bed of unbleached cotton, rest one hundred and seven small charms — wooden carvings of animals and household objects, tiny brass bells, polished river-stones with characters scratched on them, small folded paper figures, a few pieces of cheap blue glass smoothed by the sea. The sack hangs from a wooden peg on the wall of the temple's children's hall, at the height of a tall child's reach, beside a low writing-desk where the temple's literate novices teach the children of the city their characters.\n\nMirumoto Hayato was a Mirumoto general of the early sixth century, a commander of three companies in the long border skirmishes against the Phoenix over the disputed villages of the high passes. By the end of his thirty-seventh year of service he had been wounded eleven times, had buried two of his three sons in battle, and had earned the favor of the Mirumoto daimyo, who proposed to elevate him to general of the entire western front. Hayato traveled to the daimyo's house, accepted the gift of a banner, and that evening sat in the daimyo's garden and watched the daimyo's youngest daughter, a girl of perhaps five years, playing with a cloth doll. He thought a long time. At dawn he laid the banner on the doll's mat, walked out of the house without speaking to anyone, walked four days to this Temple of Hotei, and asked to be received. He took nothing with him but his under-robe and a small bag in which he carried his razors and a comb. The Mirumoto daimyo did not contest his refusal; some say the daimyo wept when he heard, but this is not certain.\n\nHayato spent the remaining twenty-nine years of his life in the temple, teaching children to read. He sewed the patch-cloth sack himself, slowly, over the first three years. The squares came from his old military garments, from the under-robes of monks who had died, from a torn obi that a passing peasant gave him, from the wrapping of a gift he had once received from his daimyo and saved. Into the sack he placed small charms — first the ones he carved himself from scraps of cedar, then the ones the children began to make and leave for him, then the ones brought by pilgrims who came to know his story. By the time of his death the sack held more than two hundred charms; the present count of one hundred and seven reflects what has been given out over the centuries.\n\nOn the first day of the Boys' Festival in spring and again on the first day of the Girls' Festival, each child who is being raised by the temple — orphans, the children of monks, the children of the city's poor whom the temple has taken in — may put a hand into the sack and draw out one charm. They may keep that charm for the year. At the next festival they return it to the sack and draw again, or they may keep what they have if Hotei has spoken clearly through it. Hayato's spirit guides the small hands; the charm drawn is the charm the child needed, and there is no shame in not understanding why for many years. Some children draw the same charm three festivals running and learn, slowly, what attachment looks like. Some draw a new charm each time and learn the lighter wisdom of letting go. Most simply receive their charm, hold it in their hand for a moment, and carry it for the year as Hotei intended.\n\nA pilgrim may not draw from the sack — it is for the children of the temple. But a pilgrim weary of strivings may petition the Custodian of Sacred Relics to *lift* the sack from its peg and feel its weight in their two hands, for one breath. The sack is unexpectedly heavy for its size; the charms shift inside it, a soft wooden rattle. Some pilgrims are graced with the sense that the weight is not the charms but the burdens Hayato laid down, and that he holds them so the pilgrim need not. Some are graced with a single charm rattling near the bottom in a particular rhythm — three soft strikes against the cloth — and the Custodian, who has heard this in others, will say that this is Hayato laughing. Most pilgrims feel only the weight and the cloth, and this is Hotei's plenty; the relic is not given to ornamenting every petition.\n\nThe sack cannot be removed from the children's hall. Its patches are repaired, never replaced; when a square wears through, a senior monk stitches a new patch over it without removing the old, and so the sack has grown slowly thicker through the centuries. The Custodian's office keeps no record of which patches are original and which are additions — Hayato did not record his own sewing, and to do so would be to make the sack into a thing of pride."}, {"slug": "sake-gourd-of-shiba-akari", "name": "The Sake Gourd of Shiba Akari", "japanese_romaji": "Akari-no-Hisago", "japanese_kanji": "灯里の瓢", "fortune": "hotei", "clan": "phoenix", "temple": "a temple of Hotei in Phoenix lands", "named_entity": "Shiba Akari (Shiba war-captain of the fourth century, who broke her bow after the war of the Yari Pass and took to brewing)", "relic_type": "vessel (sake gourd)", "description": "A dried gourd of pale green-gold, the size of a small child's head, polished smooth by long handling. Its narrow neck is bound with a band of hempen cord; its mouth is stoppered with a plug of pale paulownia wood. Along one side of the gourd's broad belly is a long, faint scar where the rind cracked once in its growing and the gourd healed itself — the temple does not consider this a flaw. The gourd rests on a low cypress stand in a small chamber off the temple's autumn courtyard, beneath a hanging scroll that bears only the character 足 (*taru*, \"enough, sufficient\") in Akari's own hand. Beside the gourd lies a single shallow sake cup of unglazed clay, the cup small enough that a full draught of it is no more than a swallow.\n\nShiba Akari served as a war-captain in the long border war of the Yari Pass in the fourth century, when the Phoenix and the Dragon disputed three villages on the western slopes. She commanded a company of bushi through eleven engagements and ended the war with a reputation for steadiness under fire. In the year following the peace, she sat in her family's house and discovered that she could not remember any of her dead by their faces — only by their voices, or the way they had moved at certain moments, and even these were beginning to fade. She broke her bow over her knee, donated her armor to the nearest Shrine of Bishamon, and walked to a small farm in the foothills where she spent the remaining forty-one years of her life brewing sake from rice she had not grown and giving most of it away. She did not return to the army. She did not marry. She took on no students. She is reported to have laughed often.\n\nThe gourd was Akari's own brewing-gourd in the last decade of her life — a vessel into which she would decant her best sake when a pilgrim of suitable misery came to her door. She would pour a single cup, drink with the pilgrim in silence, refill the cup once, and then send the pilgrim home with the gourd's blessing but without the gourd. The gourd never left her farm in her lifetime. After her death the gourd was found stoppered and full, and the village headsman brought it to this Temple of Hotei, where the Custodian of that generation tasted from it — the sake was excellent, and undimmed by the years. The gourd has been refilled each autumn since, and at each refilling some portion of the new brew is poured back into the gourd's mouth to mingle with what remains.\n\nOn the seventh day of the ninth month, the Custodian of Sacred Relics performs the **Autumn Refilling**, in which the gourd is unstoppered and a new brew — sake offered by the local Shiba families whose bushi have died in the preceding year — is poured into it. The names of the dead are read aloud as the sake is poured. The gourd does not overflow, though more sake is added each year than is drunk from it; the Custodian's office does not test this directly, for to measure the gourd would be to ask it a question it has not chosen to be asked. After the refilling, the gourd is stoppered and returned to its stand.\n\nA widow or widower of a Shiba bushi may petition the Custodian for the **Cup of Sufficiency**. The Custodian unstoppers the gourd in the petitioner's presence and pours a single small cup — never more, never less. The petitioner drinks. The Custodian asks only one question: *\"Is it enough?\"* The petitioner may answer or remain silent; either is a complete answer. Some petitioners are graced with the cup tasting unmistakably of the year of their marriage — the rice their lost husband or wife had grown, or the brew that had been served at their wedding feast. Some are graced with a warmth in the cup that lingers in their hand for the walk home, longer than wood and clay should hold heat. Some taste only good sake, and this too is Akari's kindness — she did not promise miracles, only that the cup would be enough. The Custodian does not ask further about the experience; what is given to the petitioner is for the petitioner alone.\n\nThe gourd is never poured for celebration, never for wedding feasts, never for any drinking but the Cup of Sufficiency. Pilgrims who request the cup for any other reason — to taste a famous sake, to test the relic's powers, to settle a wager — are refused without ceremony, and the Custodian does not record their names. Akari did not pour for those who were not yet finished with their wanting.\n\nThe gourd cannot be removed from the temple. The local Phoenix families have at times asked that the gourd be carried to the homes of dying old bushi for the Cup of Sufficiency to be poured in their last days — and the Custodian has, on rare occasion, permitted this when the bushi could not be moved to the temple. In each such case the gourd has returned the same evening, and the brew within has not lessened by more than the cup drunk. There is no replica. The temple workshop produces small wooden cups, sealed with the temple's mark, which Shiba families keep on the household altars of bushi who have died in service; these cups are filled with the family's own sake at festivals, and Akari is said to watch over the small drinkings as well as the great ones."}, {"slug": "wooden-top-of-asako-noritsuna", "name": "The Wooden Top of Asako Noritsuna", "japanese_romaji": "Noritsuna-no-Koma", "japanese_kanji": "紀綱の独楽", "fortune": "hotei", "clan": "phoenix", "temple": "a temple of Hotei in Phoenix lands", "named_entity": "Asako Noritsuna (Asako scholar of the fifth century, who gave away his property after the death of his small son)", "relic_type": "implement (child's wooden spinning top)", "description": "A small wooden spinning top, the height of a man's thumb-joint, turned from a single piece of pale cherrywood and balanced on an iron point set into its base. Around its widest circumference, four faint bands of pigment circle the wood — once red, blue, green, and yellow, now so worn that the colors can only be told apart when the top is held close to a lamp. The point is slightly dulled with use, and the top no longer spins perfectly true; one watches it wobble slightly as it slows, and the wobble was already present in Noritsuna's last years. The top rests on a small square of dark silk inside a shallow cypress box on a low altar in the temple's family-petitions chamber. The box has no lid; the top is always visible, and may be touched by petitioners who have been received by the Custodian.\n\nAsako Noritsuna was a scholar of the Asako family in the fifth century, a researcher in the Phoenix tradition of family genealogies and a man of moderate property — a small house in the provincial town, three rice fields rented to tenant farmers, a household of seven servants. He married late and had one child, a boy named only in the family records as \"the small one,\" who lived four years and died in the summer fever of Noritsuna's forty-eighth year. The boy had loved his spinning top, which Noritsuna had carved for him with his own hands in the boy's third year — an unusual gift in that Noritsuna was not a craftsman and the top is not a fine piece of work. In the year after the boy's death Noritsuna gave away his rice fields, dismissed his servants with generous pensions, sold his house to the Asako lineage, and walked to this temple with the top in his sleeve. He did not become a monk; the Custodian of that generation suggested that he might, but Noritsuna said only that he had given enough away already and did not wish to give away his sorrow too. He lived in a rented room near the temple for the remaining nineteen years of his life, ate one meal a day, and walked the gardens. He spoke kindly to the children of the town, but he did not teach them, and he did not carve another top. On the day of his death he left the top on the altar of the temple with a folded paper that read only: *\"For other small ones, and their parents.\"* The Custodian placed it in the cypress box where it now rests.\n\nThe petition of the top is for parents — almost always for parents, though occasionally for an elder sibling or a grandparent who has the rearing of a child. A parent who is exhausted by an unruly child, or who has lost a small child to fever or accident, or who fears they cannot love the child they have been given, may petition the Custodian of Sacred Relics for the **Spinning**. The Custodian receives the petitioner at the altar, lifts the top from its silk square, and offers it to them. The petitioner takes the top between their thumb and forefinger, sets it on the polished cypress board that lies beside the box, and spins it. The petitioner watches the top until it falls. The Custodian does not speak during the spinning.\n\nHotei's wisdom comes through the wobble. A top that spins long and falls late — many breaths, the wobble small until the final moment — is a sign that the parent's love is steady though they may not feel it; the child will outgrow what the parent fears, and patience is rewarded. A top that spins briefly and falls quickly is a sign that the parent is being asked to release some part of what they are holding — a hope, a fear, a grudge against a circumstance — and to find lightness with what remains. A top that wobbles wildly from the first turn and falls almost at once is Hotei's particular kindness to the grief-stricken: the parent is being told that they may set down the weight that is breaking them, and that the small one is already at peace and does not require their suffering. A top that spins, falls, and rolls some distance before stopping is a sign that the answer is not yet ready and the parent should return in another season. The Custodian interprets the falling, but does not add to it; the petitioner is free to receive the sign in whatever way Hotei has prepared them to receive it, and Custodians of the past century have noted that parents most often understand the falling before they are told.\n\nSome parents are graced with the top spinning unusually long — twice or three times what a child's casual spin would give. Some are graced with the top, in falling, coming to rest with its iron point exactly upon a knot in the cypress board, in a balanced posture that should not be possible. Some weep before the top has fallen, without knowing why, and the Custodian brings them a cup of warm rice-water and sits with them. Most parents see a small wobbling top spin and fall as small wobbling tops do, and this is no failure of the relic — Hotei does not crowd every petition with marvels, and the spinning itself is often the gift, for the parent has been required by the petition to hold still and watch a small turning thing for the length of its turning, which is a thing most parents in their daily lives no longer remember how to do.\n\nThe petition is permitted once per year per parent. A parent who returns within the year is gently turned away; Noritsuna gave the top for sorrow that lasts, and a year's spacing is what Hotei has chosen. The fee for the petition is a single small object that the petitioner has carried — a hair-pin, a button, a folded paper, a loose tooth from the child, an unimportant coin — which the Custodian places in a tall cedar jar kept beside the altar. The jar is emptied once a generation into the river that runs past the temple, and the things are released; Noritsuna's spirit has charge of them, and tends to them in the river's slow Hotei-ish way.\n\nThe top cannot be removed from the temple. It is not repaired; the iron point is dulled and will continue to dull, the colors are worn and will continue to wear, and when the day comes — the temple does not yet know when — that the top can no longer spin, the temple will receive a new sign from Hotei about what to do. The Custodian's office produces no replica tops for sale. Parents who wish to take something home from the petition may, with the Custodian's permission, take a single shaving of cherrywood from the box's silk square — there is always a small handful of such shavings under the top, where they have collected over the centuries from the wood's slow surrender, and the temple does not know quite where they come from but accepts the supply as Noritsuna's continuing generosity."}, {"slug": "decade-beads-of-shosuro-emiko", "name": "The Decade Beads of Shosuro Emiko", "japanese_romaji": "Junen-Juzu", "japanese_kanji": "十年数珠", "fortune": "jurojin", "clan": "scorpion", "temple": "a temple of Jurojin in Scorpion lands", "named_entity": "Shosuro Emiko (Scorpion widow of the late third century, who outlived her husband by sixty-one years and kept the count of her widowhood on these beads)", "relic_type": "implement (prayer beads numbered by decade)", "description": "A string of one hundred and eight prayer beads, larger and more deliberately spaced than the ordinary monastic *juzu*, the beads carved from polished cypress and strung on a heavy silk cord the color of dried iris. Among the hundred and eight are nine larger beads of darker wood, set at regular intervals — one larger bead for every twelve smaller — and a single bead of pale river-pearl at the place where the cord knots into its tassel. The decade-markers are stained darker than the rest from being passed many thousands of times between Emiko's thumb and forefinger over the sixty-one years she carried them. The beads rest in a shallow cedar tray on a low table in a quiet alcove off the temple's bereavement hall, beside an unlit oil lamp that is lit only when the beads are in use.\n\nShosuro Emiko was a widow of the late third century. Her husband, Shosuro Hidetake, fell in his thirty-second year in a duel whose particulars are no longer recorded in the family register. Emiko was twenty-nine. She did not remarry, despite three serious proposals during her thirties and one again in her fifties; she kept her husband's household, raised their two daughters, served three Shosuro daimyo as a senior lady-in-waiting, and lived to her ninetieth year. She had commissioned the beads in her thirty-second year, the year after Hidetake's death, from a Shosuro craftsman who carved the cypress from a tree felled on the day of her wedding. She began the count of her widowhood on the night of the year-day of his death, telling one full circuit of the beads — one hundred and eight passes of the cord — and marking the first decade-bead with a single touch of red ink at the end of the year. She continued the practice each year for sixty-one years. The decade-beads bear faint traces of the red ink to this day, layered into a deep stain at each marker.\n\nEmiko's last surviving daughter brought the beads to the temple after her mother's death, with a written note: *for those who must yet count out their own years*.\n\nA pilgrim who has lost a spouse, a parent, or a beloved companion within the past year may petition the Custodian of Sacred Relics to take up the beads for one telling. The Custodian receives the pilgrim at the bereavement hall, lights the oil lamp, and places the beads in the pilgrim's hands. The pilgrim is asked to tell one full circuit — one hundred and eight passes — counting each bead aloud or in silence as they prefer, and naming the lost one once at each decade-bead. The Custodian sits across from them in silence and does not speak unless spoken to. A full telling takes most pilgrims between a quarter-hour and an hour, depending on the steadiness of their hands and the depth of their grief.\n\nThe beads carry the steadiness of Emiko's count. Some pilgrims are graced with finding the decade-beads warm beneath their thumb where the surrounding beads are cool — an auspicious omen that Emiko has set her thumb beside theirs and that the count has been joined to hers. Some are graced with the lamp's flame steadying noticeably during the telling, where before the pilgrim's breath had set it dancing, and this is taken as Jurojin's particular attention to those whose breath has begun to ease. Some find that the count seems shorter than they had expected, the hundred and eight passing more quickly than the time of an hourglass ought to allow, and this is taken as a sign that the patience of the years to come may yet pass more quickly than the bereaved had feared. Most pilgrims simply tell the beads and feel their grief no less than before, and even this is the gift — for to count to one hundred and eight in the presence of one who counted to over six thousand is to be reminded that grief has a tempo, and the tempo continues.\n\nAt the conclusion of the telling, the Custodian asks the pilgrim a single question: *will you return in a year?* The pilgrim is not required to answer. If they answer yes, their name is entered into the *Roll of Counted Years*, which has been kept since the beads came to the temple. Each year-day of the loss, the pilgrim may return and tell one further circuit; their name is marked in the roll with the new decade-bead they have reached in their own widowhood or bereavement. Those who reach the ninth decade-bead — sixty years of accumulated tellings — are entered in the temple's permanent records and remembered in the year-end prayers. In the four centuries the beads have been at the temple, eleven names have reached the ninth.\n\nThe beads cannot be removed from the bereavement hall. The cord has been replaced twice — silk does not last sixty years of daily handling, much less four centuries of intermittent — but the beads themselves are the same beads Emiko commissioned, the same cypress from the tree felled on the day of her wedding. The river-pearl at the tassel was added by Emiko's own hand in her eightieth year, the year she stopped her own daily telling and laid the beads aside; the dates of the cord-replacements are not recorded, for the cord is the servant of the beads and not the relic itself."}, {"slug": "ever-lit-lantern-of-the-broken-house", "name": "The Ever-Lit Lantern of the Broken House", "japanese_romaji": "Tomoshibi-no-Toro", "japanese_kanji": "灯し火の燈籠", "fortune": "jurojin", "clan": "scorpion", "temple": "a temple of Jurojin in Scorpion lands", "named_entity": "Shosuro Genbei (Bayushi-vassal merchant, who outlived all seven of his children and ran his trading house into its second century)", "relic_type": "stone lantern (continuously lit)", "description": "A stone lantern of grey andesite, the height of a kneeling man, set on a low platform of river-rock in the temple's inner courtyard. The lantern's hood is carved with the seven petals of an autumn chrysanthemum; its body bears seven small windows, one for each of Genbei's lost children, and within burns a single oil-lamp wick of twisted hemp, fed from a brass reservoir at the lantern's base. The lantern has been continuously lit for one hundred and fourteen years. The Custodian of the Lamp, a senior monk appointed for life, sleeps in a small cell that opens directly onto the courtyard, so that the lantern may be tended at any hour. A second monk, the *vice-custodian*, sleeps in a cell on the opposite side; if both the lamp and one custodian were to fail in the same night, the second would yet be at hand.\n\nShosuro Genbei was a Bayushi-vassal merchant of Ryoko Owari, who established his trading house in his twenty-third year and lived to manage it until his hundred-and-third. He had seven children by his first wife and three by his second; the first wife predeceased him, the second wife predeceased him, and all seven of the first wife's children predeceased him as well — three to plague, two to childbed, one to a duel he had not been told of until the body was returned, and one to old age in her seventieth year, herself outlived by her father. The three children of the second wife survived him. In his ninetieth year, Genbei commissioned the lantern and the cell beside it, and gave to the temple a perpetual endowment from the trading house's books to maintain the lamp and the Custodian's sustenance. The terms of the endowment specify that should the trading house fail, the temple is to draw upon the principal until the principal is exhausted, and only then to extinguish the flame. The trading house has not failed; it is now in its second century, run by Genbei's great-grandson, and the principal has not been touched.\n\nThe lantern is the focus of the *Watch of Continuing Days*, a continuous vigil maintained by the temple. The Custodian of the Lamp checks the wick and the reservoir at the hour of the dog each evening and at the hour of the tiger each morning; the vice-custodian checks at the hour of the rat. The lamp has not gone out. Once, in the great storm of the fifty-eighth year of its lighting, the flame was reported as dim for nearly an hour; the Custodian of that generation knelt at the platform through the night and replaced the wick three times in succession, and the flame did not fail. He wrote in his journal afterward that Jurojin had not so much sustained the flame as sustained *him*, that he might sustain the flame.\n\nA pilgrim who has buried a child — of any age, infant or grown adult, of their body or of their household — may petition the temple to keep a single watch at the lantern. The petition is granted in order of receipt, with no preference given to rank; the Bayushi daimyo himself, when one of his sons fell in the Lion border-skirmish of seventy years past, waited eleven days for his turn. The watch is kept from the hour of the dog to the hour of the tiger, the pilgrim seated on a low cushion on the courtyard stones, the Custodian present but silent. Jurojin, who himself has buried generations beyond counting, does not require speech of those who keep the watch.\n\nSome pilgrims are graced with the flame steadying after their arrival, where before it had wavered in the night air — a singular omen that Genbei has acknowledged the pilgrim's loss and joined his grief to theirs. Some are graced with finding, at the hour of the tiger, that the seven windows of the lantern have each shown a clear unflickering light, where ordinarily one or two will flicker with the night's breath — and this is taken as a sign that the pilgrim's lost one has been received among Genbei's seven, and is no longer alone. Some hear, in the small hours, the soft sound of a brush moving across paper, as of an old man working over his ledgers, and this is the merchant himself attending to the accounts of the living. Most pilgrims feel only the cold of the stones and the slow turning of the night, and even this is enough — for a parent who has kept one watch at the lantern of the Broken House has been told, without words, that the bearing of such losses is a labor that has been borne before, and that one may yet rise from the cushion at dawn and continue.\n\nThe lantern cannot be extinguished. The terms of Genbei's endowment are unalterable in the temple's records, and successive Bayushi daimyo have confirmed them at the changing of each generation. Were the flame to go out, the temple is bound to relight it immediately from the secondary lamp kept ready in the Custodian's cell, and to record the lapse in the *Book of the Watch* — a book which contains, in one hundred and fourteen years, only the single entry from the great storm of the fifty-eighth year, and no other."}, {"slug": "grave-tablet-of-soshi-narimichi", "name": "The Grave Tablet of Soshi Narimichi", "japanese_romaji": "Narimichi-no-Ihai", "japanese_kanji": "業道の位牌", "fortune": "jurojin", "clan": "scorpion", "temple": "a temple of Jurojin in Scorpion lands", "named_entity": "Soshi Narimichi (Scorpion shugenja who returned alive from the Burning Sands after thirty-one years, and lived to his hundred-and-second year)", "relic_type": "funeral implement (ancestral memorial tablet)", "description": "A wooden funeral tablet of dark walnut, the length of a forearm, narrow and unadorned save for the posthumous name *Joen-in Choju Koji* (淨園院長寿居士, \"Layman of the Pure Garden, Long Life\") inscribed down its face in lacquer ink, and the dates of Narimichi's birth and death cut into the reverse with a fine knife. The tablet stands upright in a small wooden tabernacle at the rear of the temple's only prayer hall, behind a low altar where a single stick of sandalwood incense is kept burning. The tabernacle door is opened at dawn and closed at sunset; the tablet is not removed from the tabernacle for any reason save the annual cleaning at the changing of the year.\n\nThe Kakkimine hermitage is a small Jurojin temple of fewer than a dozen monks, established eight generations past on the eastern flank of the highlands that wall off Ryoko Owari from the Dragon border. The temple was founded by Soshi Narimichi himself in his eighty-seventh year, after he had outlived every member of the expedition with which he had set out into the Sands six decades before. He had been a young Scorpion shugenja, one of those who had crossed westward in the first century of the Unicorn's absence, on a mission whose precise charge is not recorded in any surviving register. He returned alone in his fifty-fifth year, thirty-one years after his departure, walking out of the eastern desert with no clear account of where the others had fallen. He took no further commission from the Scorpion. He lived quietly in Ryoko Owari for thirty more years, and in his eighty-seventh year withdrew to the highlands and built the hermitage with the help of three young monks who attended him. He died in his hundred-and-second year, having lived more years after his return than he had lived before his departure.\n\nThe tablet was inscribed by Narimichi himself in his hundredth year, with his own choice of posthumous name and the date of his birth. The date of his death he left blank, to be filled in by the monk who would receive him; the cut on the reverse is in the hand of his successor, the first Custodian of the hermitage.\n\nThe hermitage is small, and its visitors are few. The Custodian of the Tablet — which office is held in this house by the senior monk after the High Monk, there being no distinction here between *Custodian of Sacred Relics* and *Custodian of the Tablet*, for there is only the one relic — receives pilgrims who have walked the four-day path from Ryoko Owari to the temple. The Custodian asks the pilgrim to spend a night in the prayer hall before the open tabernacle, to speak the names of their own dead aloud once each, and to sit until dawn.\n\nThe petition is offered most commonly by those whose families have outlived themselves — a samurai who is the last of their lineage, a widow whose children have all preceded her, a household elder who has signed the funeral documents of every cousin of their generation. Jurojin's gift to such pilgrims is not the restoration of what they have lost, but the patience to bear what remains; Narimichi, who walked alone out of the Sands and built the temple in his eighty-seventh year, understood this gift more deeply than any other servant of the Fortune in the Scorpion lands.\n\nSome pilgrims are graced with a slow steadying of the incense smoke during the night — the smoke ordinarily curls and wavers, but during the watches before dawn it may rise straight in a single column from the stick, and this is taken as an auspicious omen that Narimichi has accepted the pilgrim's vigil and recognized in them a successor to his patience. Some are graced with the smell of damp sand and far-off wind in the prayer hall, the smell of the desert from which Narimichi returned, and this is taken as the shugenja's particular acknowledgment of those who have made similar long crossings of their own. Some pilgrims hear nothing and feel nothing through the night, and even this is no failure; Narimichi himself, in the writings he left to the hermitage, recorded that the gift of the night is the night itself, and that those who require further sign are not yet ready for the gift's deeper portion.\n\nThe pilgrim, on departing at dawn, is given a small wooden token by the Custodian — a sliver cut from the same walnut tree from which Narimichi's tablet was carved, of which the hermitage keeps a careful stock. The token is to be placed on the pilgrim's family altar beside the tablets of their own dead, where Narimichi will attend them.\n\nThe tablet does not leave the hermitage. The walnut tree from which it was cut still stands in the small grove behind the prayer hall, having outlived Narimichi by eight generations. The hermitage's records do not speculate on the tree's age; what is known is that Narimichi planted no tree, and that the tree was old when he arrived. The tokens are cut sparingly, that the tree may continue."}, {"slug": "knotted-cane-of-old-tarobei", "name": "The Knotted Cane of Old Tarobei", "japanese_romaji": "Fushi-no-Tsue", "japanese_kanji": "節の杖", "fortune": "jurojin", "clan": "any", "temple": "a temple of Jurojin, in any city of the Empire", "named_entity": "Tarobei (peasant farmer of the Yasen plain, who survived three famines and lived to his ninety-seventh year)", "relic_type": "implement (walking cane)", "description": "A short walking cane of mulberry wood, dark and oil-blackened from a lifetime of handling, the length of a man's arm from elbow to fingertip. The wood is gnarled with eleven distinct knots along its length, and Tarobei is said to have rested his thumb on a different knot each year of his old age, beginning with the lowest in his eighty-seventh year and ending with the highest in his ninety-seventh. The grip-end is bound in faded indigo cloth, replaced by the wife of the village headsman each spring; the foot is shod with a small iron cap, the third such cap, the previous two having worn through. The cane stands in a wooden rack against the wall of a side chamber off the temple's almsgiving hall, beside a low cushion where elderly pilgrims may sit.\n\nTarobei was a peasant farmer of the Yasen plain who lived through three famines — the Long Snow of his eleventh year, the Yellow Summer of his forty-second, and the Locust Year of his seventy-fourth. He buried his parents, his wife, two of his three children, and four of his six grandchildren. He continued to work his rice paddy until his ninety-third year, when his great-granddaughter took the work from him and gave him the cane in its stead. He had cut the cane himself from a mulberry tree in his father's hedge in his sixtieth year, but had not used it until his ninety-third, having said that the cane was for his old age and his old age had not yet arrived. He died in his ninety-seventh year, sitting in the doorway of his hut at dusk, and the village said only that he had finally finished his work. The cane was brought to the temple by his great-granddaughter, who herself died two winters later in her sixty-third year, having outlived her brothers and her husband and three of her children.\n\nA pilgrim who has buried a child, a spouse, or both parents, and who is uncertain whether they have the strength to continue living, may petition the *Shika* — the Steward of Hospitality, in the temple's old usage — to sit for an afternoon with the cane. The Shika opens the rack, lifts the cane down, and places it across the pilgrim's lap. The pilgrim sits on the cushion until the sun has moved one hand's breadth across the floor of the chamber. There are no prayers prescribed; Jurojin attends those who simply remain.\n\nThe cane carries the weight of Tarobei's work. Some pilgrims are graced with finding the wood warm where their hand has rested on it, though the chamber is cool and the cane was cold when placed across their lap — an auspicious omen, a sign that Tarobei has recognized the pilgrim's burden and lent them a measure of his endurance for the season to come. Some are graced with the smell of cut rice-straw in the chamber, though no rice has been harvested nearby in months, and this is taken as the old farmer's particular blessing on those who must yet return to their fields. Some weep quietly without knowing why, and the Shika does not disturb them; the cane has carried many such weepings, and it knows how to bear them. Most pilgrims feel only the wood and the slow turn of the light, and even this is a kindness — for a samurai or a peasant who has sat one afternoon with the cane of a man who outlived three famines has been reminded that survival is itself a labor, and a labor that has been done before may be done again.\n\nThe cane is also brought out at the *Year-Turning Petition*, observed at the temple on the first morning after the winter solstice. Elderly pilgrims of the city come in procession, each touching the cane once and naming aloud the year they have just completed. The Shika records each name and year in the temple's ledger, which has been kept since the cane arrived — three centuries of names, accumulating from the foot of the page to the top in each generation's hand. Those whose names appear in the ledger for ten consecutive years are given a small wooden token from the temple workshop, carved with the character 寿 (*kotobuki*, \"longevity\") and the year of their tenth attestation, to be placed on their family altar.\n\nThe cane does not leave the temple. The iron cap has been replaced when worn through, and the indigo cloth is replaced each spring, but the mulberry shaft is the same wood that Tarobei cut from his father's hedge in his sixtieth year. To replace the wood would be to lose what the wood carries; the temple's records do not name the dates of the cap-replacements, for such records would suggest a relic that is *maintained* rather than *given*."}, {"slug": "long-shell-of-bayushi-akemi", "name": "The Long Shell of Bayushi Akemi", "japanese_romaji": "Nagaki-no-Kora", "japanese_kanji": "長きの甲羅", "fortune": "jurojin", "clan": "scorpion", "temple": "a temple of Jurojin in Scorpion lands", "named_entity": "Bayushi Akemi (Scorpion courtier of the late fourth century, who outlived four daimyo and every rival she ever knew)", "relic_type": "natural object (turtle-shell amulet)", "description": "The shell of a mountain turtle, the size of a woman's open hand, polished so that the dark plates of its back catch the lamplight like wet stone. Along the rim a thread of pale silk has been knotted through five small holes drilled by Akemi's own hand; from the silk depends a single carved bead of bone, which the old courtier kept against her breast for sixty-two years. The shell rests on a black-lacquered tray in a narrow chamber off the temple's eastern colonnade, beside a brass stand on which a brazier of long-burning charcoal is kept warm at all hours. The chamber smells of pine resin and old ink.\n\nBayushi Akemi was a courtier of the late fourth century, and the longest-lived woman of her generation in the Bayushi house. She entered the Scorpion court in her seventeenth year and did not leave it until her ninety-first, having served four daimyo of the Scorpion in succession. She had no children of her own, no husband whose name survives in the family records, and no enemies left living to mourn her — a circumstance she is reported to have remarked upon in her final winter with neither pleasure nor regret. The shell she carried she had taken from the riverbank of the Drowned Merchant's Tributary on the day of her gempukku, when an old turtle had hauled itself up onto the stones to die. Akemi remarked that the shell would carry her past her enemies as it had carried its first owner past many seasons, and she fastened it to her sash that same evening.\n\nThe shell came to the temple by the bequest of her granddaughter-in-law, who had received it from Akemi's hand on the night before the old courtier's death. The bequest noted only: *for those who would yet endure*.\n\nA pilgrim who has come to know that their position is unsafe — a courtier whose patron has fallen, a magistrate who has ruled against a powerful house, a samurai whose name has begun to appear in the wrong correspondence — may petition the Custodian of Sacred Relics to keep vigil with the shell for one night. The Custodian receives the pilgrim in the chamber at the hour of the dog, places the shell on a folded silk cloth before them, and withdraws. The pilgrim sits before the brazier and the shell until the hour of the tiger, neither speaking nor sleeping. Jurojin, Fortune of long life, attends those who would learn his patience.\n\nSome pilgrims are graced with finding the shell warm to the touch at the changing of the watch, though the brazier is set far enough away that the shell should be only as warm as the room — an auspicious omen that Akemi has accepted the vigil and recognized the pilgrim as her successor in patience. Some are graced with a single clear thought about which of their adversaries will not outlive them, and they leave the chamber knowing where to direct their care and where to spend none. Some hear, in the small hours, the faint scrape of a turtle's claws against stone, and the Custodian when he returns finds them composed in a way they were not when they entered. Most pilgrims experience no remarkable sign, and the night of stillness is itself the gift — for a samurai who has sat one night with their own peril and not fled it has already begun to outlast it.\n\nThe shell does not permit haste. Pilgrims who have asked to keep vigil with it twice in the same season are gently turned away by the Custodian; Jurojin's patience is not a resource to be drawn upon, only a stream to be entered when one is ready to enter it. The bone bead has been replaced twice in the centuries since Akemi's death — the silk thread perishes with handling, and a replacement bead is carved by a senior monk and blessed at the brazier — but the temple's records do not identify which bead is current. What matters is the shell, which is the same shell that crawled out of the river the year Akemi came of age, and the patience of which the bead is only the small bright reminder.\n\nThe shell cannot be removed from the temple. The Bayushi house has petitioned three times across the centuries to have it travel to a daimyo's deathbed, and three times the Custodian has refused — Jurojin's gift is in the pilgrim coming to the shell, not in the shell coming to the pilgrim, and a daimyo who could not walk to the chamber has by then passed beyond the reach of the relic's particular consolation. The refusals were each accepted; in the Scorpion, even the daimyo understands that some gifts must be earned by the journey to them."}, {"slug": "mortar-of-the-five-generations", "name": "The Mortar of the Five Generations", "japanese_romaji": "Goshu-no-Suribachi", "japanese_kanji": "五代の擂鉢", "fortune": "jurojin", "clan": "unicorn", "temple": "a temple of Jurojin in Unicorn lands", "named_entity": "Iuchi Sarukichi (Unicorn apothecary who returned from the Burning Sands and treated five generations of the Shinjo household)", "relic_type": "implement (apothecary's mortar and pestle)", "description": "A wide-mouthed mortar of dark-fired clay, the size of a melon, glazed on the inside with the pale grey film of a thousand grindings of herb and bone. The pestle that rests within it is of pale unfinished oak, worn smooth and slightly curved by Sarukichi's right hand and the right hands of his three apprentices in succession. The grooves on the mortar's inner surface are barely visible to the eye but unmistakable to the touch, faint radiating lines worn by the pestle along its accustomed arc. The mortar rests on a wooden stand in a small chamber off the temple's hospice wing, where the sick of the city are received; the chamber smells of dried angelica and ginseng even when neither herb is being prepared, the long residue of Sarukichi's work having soaked into the wood of the walls.\n\nIuchi Sarukichi was an apothecary in the train of Shinjo Otokwan, one of the families that crossed the Burning Sands and returned in the great homecoming. He had begun his apprenticeship in the herb-gardens of the old Iuchi house before the crossing, and was already past his fortieth year when the families set out. He survived the Sands, returned with the Unicorn, and on his arrival took up the post of household apothecary to the Shinjo daimyo, a post he held for the next sixty-three years. He treated the daimyo who had received him, that daimyo's son, that son's son, that son's son's son, and the infant grandson of the fourth — five generations of the same line. He had taken three apprentices in succession, of whom two predeceased him and the third inherited his practice. He died in his hundred-and-eighth year, having missed only nine days of work in the sixty-three years of his Shinjo service, and the mortar he had brought back from the Sands was given to the temple by his last apprentice, who specified only that it be kept where the sick might be near it.\n\nThe mortar holds the long alignment of an apothecary's life with Jurojin's domain. Sarukichi himself, in the only writings of his that survive, recorded that the herbs of longevity must be ground by a hand that has touched the same grindings many times, for the spirit of the herb knows its own road and grows confused when the road is changed. The pestle is the same pestle Sarukichi shaped from a sapling on the eastern slopes of the Sands, after the original pestle was lost in the crossing; the mortar is the original mortar he brought from the Iuchi gardens before the crossing, and is therefore older than the Unicorn's return.\n\nBefore any longevity tonic is prepared for a difficult patient at the temple hospice — for an elder facing their eightieth winter, for a samurai whose wounds have not closed despite ordinary care, for a child whose breath has been weak from birth — the temple's senior physician, who serves as Custodian of the Mortar, performs the *First Grinding*. He takes a single root of ginseng, places it in the mortar, and works it once around its arc with the pestle. He then sets the pestle aside, removes the root, and proceeds with the rest of the preparation using a working mortar of the hospice's ordinary stock. Sarukichi's grinding has joined itself to the day's work, and the patient's tonic is thereby brought into the long road of his practice.\n\nSome patients are graced with the recovery proceeding faster than the senior physician would have predicted from his examination — a sign that Sarukichi has recognized the patient as he recognized his old daimyos, and lent the practice of those treatments to the new one. Some patients are graced with the chamber smelling unusually strong of angelica on the morning of their preparation, though no angelica has been ground there in some weeks, and this is taken as Sarukichi's particular attention. Some recoveries do not proceed; Jurojin's patience is for those whose time he has chosen to extend, and the relic is not a guarantor but an attendant. The senior physician records each preparation in the *Hospice Register* with the date, the patient's name, and the herb worked at the First Grinding, but does not attempt to record outcomes; outcomes belong to Jurojin, and the register's purpose is the maintenance of the practice, not its measurement.\n\nThe mortar cannot be removed from the hospice chamber. Sarukichi's last apprentice was specific in his bequest: the relic is to remain where the sick may be near it, and is to attend the hospice's preparations as Sarukichi attended his daimyo's household. A traveling Shinjo physician who wishes the mortar's blessing on a particular case is given, instead, a small clay token from the hospice — fired from the same earth as the mortar's body, glazed with a single grey stripe — which they carry in their satchel and place beside the working mortar of their own practice. The pestle has been re-shaped twice in the centuries since Sarukichi's death, as oak does not last forever; the hospice's records do not name the dates of the re-shapings, for the curve of the pestle is given by the work it does, and a freshly shaped pestle returns to the same curve within a season of use."}]};
